<SECOND>BC-North Trial-Testimony, 1st Add,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: those questions.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUDGE GESELL: Well, now, colonel, that would require going to
the president, wouldn't it? ... Did you understand you had the
power to assert executive privilege for the president?
   NORTH: It was my understanding, sir, that executive privilege
could be exerted.
   JUDGE GESELL: By the president?
   NORTH: Well, by the office of the presidency, yes, sir.
   (There followed an exchange describing concerns by North about
the response to Congress suggested by McFarlane, including concern
about the disclosure of clandestine ammunition shipments to the
Contras.)
   NORTH: I was disturbed that the answer he was going to give,
given what the press was saying, the media was out there reporting
in volumes on what was going on down in Central America, and all
this was going to do was add, you know, fuel to the fire. It was
like throwing gasoline on the fire. In fact, it ended up that way.
... My point was, this answer that you (McFarlane) are proposing is
not going to help us. It is not going to help get the job done. It
is not going to help get aid to the resistance. It is just going to
make things worse.
   SULLIVAN: Did Mr. McFarlane reject your advice then with respect
to the draft that he had made?
   NORTH: Yes, sir, he did.
   JUDGE GESELL: What did he say, colonel?
   NORTH: My recollection is, sir, that he said that he had talked
with the president about the approach we were taking on the letters
and that my approach was far too confrontational. ...
   SULLIVAN: Congressman Barnes received a response to his letter
at about the same time, didn't he?
   NORTH: Yes, sir. ...
   SULLIVAN: Was ... Congressman Barnes' letter ... similar to the
Hamilton letter?
   NORTH: Yes, sir, it is.
   (North refers to several additional inquiries from Barnes and
Hamilton and that McFarlane briefed the congressman.)
   SULLIVAN: Now, after then, in order, two letters _ these letters
had been sent by Mr. McFarlane, two to Hamilton, one to Barnes?
   NORTH: Right.
   SULLIVAN: He (McFarlane) had been up to Capitol Hill twice?
   NORTH: Yes. ... There was a fairly steady flow of paper from Mr.
Barnes asking for documents, yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: What are you telling Mr. McFarlane that he should do
with respect to Barnes' further inquiry ... ?
   NORTH: What I said was that I had attached a letter from Mr.
McFarlane back to Congressman Barnes in response to his request for
documents. ... (I) told Mr. McFarlane to remind Mr. Barnes that the
classified letter he had sent earlier had been revealed to the
media.
   SULLIVAN: ... Is this your draft that you recommended McFarlane
send to Barnes? (in response to the inquiries.)
   NORTH: Yes, sir, it is.
   SULLIVAN: Does your draft give Barnes what he wants or what he
is asking for?
   NORTH: No, sir, it does not.
   SULLIVAN: Does it take a hard line position saying, in essence,
that the information should not be given?
   NORTH: Yes, sir, it takes the approach of executive privilege.
...
   SULLIVAN: In essence, you are telling him we are not going to
give you documents?
   NORTH: We are not going to give you documents and here is why.
   (North says his draft letter was never sent.)
   SULLIVAN: So that you never did get your way in recommending
that the executive branch simply say to Congress, we have a right
not to provide information?
   NORTH: No, sir, I didn't. ... He (McFarlane) did call me over to
his office and showed me this stack of documents, which I at that
point did not realize was sitting over in his office. I know I was
surprised that they were there but not shocked. I mean, they were
his documents.
   SULLIVAN: Tell the jury what happened in that meeting with
regard to these documents.
   NORTH: Mr. McFarlane showed me the pile of documents and said,
there are several in here that are _ my recollection of the word is
problematical, that this handful, and he had pulled out several,
are a problem and they are inconsistent with what we have said to
the Congress. And certainly they were. I think he handed them to me
and I looked at them. And they were documents that clearly showed
what I had been doing at his direction in Central America. ... And
he said, these need to be fixed. In fact, he handed me a list that
had those documents on it and, as I recall, also cited several
others that I wrote down on the back of that list. He gave me that
list and said, fix these documents so that they are consistent with
what we have basically told the Congress.
   SULLIVAN: Did you explain to him right there at the time that it
didn't make sense to change any documents because the files were
filled with similar documents?
   NORTH: Yes, I did.
   SULLIVAN: What was his response to that?
   NORTH: He just told me to fix the documents and I mean, what's
important, those were his documents. I had written them all. But
they were his documents.
   SULLIVAN: What happened to the request that he made to change
documents? Did it just sit there?
   NORTH: Basically it did. ...
   SULLIVAN: So why didn't you do what he said?
   NORTH: Because I just didn't _ I didn't think it made any sense.
(A year later when North was about to be dismissed, he said he
altered the document.)
   SULLIVAN: That was in November 1986?
   NORTH: Yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: Did you believe it was unlawful to do that?
   NORTH: No, I had written those documents. I had prepared them
for him. They were his documents. It never occurred to me that that
could be unlawful.
</TEXT>
