<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0616EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Consulate     04-08 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consulate,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Accuses Soviets of Eavesdropping, Issues Angry Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union bugged the U.S. Consulate in
Leningrad, the State Department charged in a statement that called
the action reprehensible no matter how long ago the listening
devices were planted.
   The State Department said Friday the listening devices were
discovered in early February during an inspection by security
personnel.
   ``Such hostile attempts at intelligence gathering, however long
ago they may have been initiated, are deeply resented by the
American people,'' the department said it had told the Soviets in a
protest.
   The devices in the consulate, which was opened in 1973, were
discovered by officers from the Bureau of Diplomatic Security, the
statement said.
   According to a U.S. official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, the devices were implanted ``deep in the structure a
long time ago.'' He declined to provide further details.
   In 1985, the United States accused the Soviets of planting
listening devices in the new U.S. embassy chancery in Moscow. In
1987, a Marine guard, Sgt. Clayton Lonetree, was accused and
court-martialed on charges he permitted Soviet intelligence agents
to gain access to the U.S. embassy.
   The latest accusation of Soviet intrusion was unexpected. The
two governments were in the process of deciding whether to open new
consulates in Kiev and New York.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, meanwhile, was in the
midst of deciding what to do about the U.S. embassy in Moscow.
   The two aides he sent there on an inspection trip returned two
weeks ago with a recommendation to salvage part of the chancery, an
administration official said Wednesday.
   The inspection was conducted by Nicholas M. Salgo, a former U.S.
ambassador to Hungary, and Ivan Selin, who has been nominated to be
undersecretary of state for management.
   They told Baker on their return that refurbishing the building
or even constructing an annex would be cheaper than razing the
chancery and starting over. The estimated cost of tearing down and
rebuilding the structure is $500 million.
   A trade group headed by Dwayne O. Andreas, chairman of Archer
Daniels Midland Co., offered to buy the building for use as
business offices.
   Andreas is co-chairman of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic
Council, which promotes trade between the two superpowers. He made
the offer on behalf of a consortium of U.S. companies, which would
use the building as a Moscow headquarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
