<FIRST>r a PM-EmbarrassedNurse     04-08 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Embarrassed Nurse,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse Says School Ridiculed Her Weight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse has sued her former instructors
for allegedly ridiculing her weight and using her as an example of
how difficult it would be to care for an obese person.
   Sharon L. Russell, now a nurse at All Children's Hospital in St.
Petersburg, Fla., sued Salve Regina College and five faculty
members contending they violated an implied contract by refusing to
let her complete school, invaded her privacy and caused her
emotional distress.
   She is seeking unspecified damages.
   Russell was told in 1985 that she would not be allowed to return
for her senior year because she had failed to lose weight over the
summer.
   Russell testified in U.S. District Court Thursday that
instructor Barbara Dean once told her there was no uniform to fit
her and said, ``You'll never make it around the bed because you're
too big.''
   Another instructor, Sister Maureen Hines, on one occasion ``had
me get into bed to show (classmates) it's more difficult to make a
bed with an overweight person in it,'' Russell said. ``I was
embarrassed and humiliated.''
   The nun also once grabbed her arm and said how difficult it was
to give an injection through obese tissue, Russell testified.
   The nurse, who completed training at St. Joseph's College in
West Hartford, Conn., in 1987, also contends the school should pay
damages because she lost a year of prospective employment.
   Steven P. Snow, the college's lawyer, said in his opening
statement that the instructors ``knew better than she knew the
physical demands that are placed upon a nurse in our society.''
   Russell suffered from an eating disorder, was more than 200
pounds overweight and could not be fitted into a ``scrub gown,''
Snow said.
   He said the six unsatisfactory marks Russell received from her
clinical instructors in 1984 all were related to her weight, but
said she was ultimately given a passing grade in return for a
promise to go on a diet.
   ``Time and time again she broke that promise,'' he said.
   Russell was allowed to register for her senior year only on the
understanding she would diet during the summer, and she did not,
Snow said.
   Salve Regina, a private college in Newport, is administered by
the Roman Catholic Sisters of Mercy.
</TEXT>
