<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial     04-08 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Says Administration Officials Knew of Hawk Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administration officials knew at the time
about a November 1985 shipment of missiles to Iran, according to
Oliver North's defense.
   During his examination Friday of North, defense attorney Brendan
Sullivan brought out that top officials were given data from
intelligence intercepts tracking the 1985 shipment almost hourly.
   North, examining one of the intercepts, noted the exact minute a
plane touched down in Iran.
   North denied, however, that he falsely stated to Congress that
no one in the U.S. government learned before 1986 that Hawk
missiles had been shipped to Iran in November 1985.
   North testified that although he was at a meeting Nov. 20, 1986,
where congressional testimony was discussed, he played no part in
shaping prepared testimony.
   According to the evidence, those receiving summaries of such
intercepts included national security adviser Robert McFarlane or
North and CIA Director William Casey or his deputy. Also receiving
them were Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger, and the chairman of
the joint chiefs of staff John Vessey and his deputy.
   Casey sat in on the Nov. 20, 1986, meeting which was intended to
prepare him and national security adviser John Poindexter for
congressional appearances on the Iran initiative the next day,
according to testimony.
   The CIA participants brought to the meeting a proposed insert
saying the spy agency had been told the shipment was oil drilling
equipment.
   The CIA had arranged, at North's request, to have one of its
airlines transport the Hawks in 1985, but did so without first
getting a presidential finding.
   North recalled that as the Iran-Contra affair unfolded in
November 1986, he spoke to his former boss, McFarlane, about the
shipment of Hawks.
   McFarlane said that it didn't happen, North said.
   ``You knew it happened?'' asked Sullivan.
   ``Yes sir,'' replied North. ``He called me up from Europe and
made it happen.''
   In testimony during North's trial, McFarlane had a different
recollection. McFarlane said North told him that ``he believed he
and I hadn't learned the precise details of what happened until''
12 months after the shipment.
   McFarlane said he doubted at the time of the 1986 conversation
that North was correct, but that his own memory of the 1985
shipment was hazy so that he couldn't contradict North.
   As a result, McFarlane said, he changed a chronology of the Iran
arms shipments, removing a reference to the November 1985 shipment
of Hawks and substituting instead a more general reference to other
transfers of equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-NorthTrial-Testimony 2ndAdd   04-08 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Trial-Testimony, 2nd Add,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: be unlawful.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SULLIVAN: When you were having the discussions with Mr.
McFarlane back in August and September of 1985 as to how to answer
these congressmen, you were arguing to him that he should not
respond. Did it ever occur to you that his response was unlawful?
   NORTH: No ... in fact, ... it never occurred to me the letter
could be a violation of the law.
   SULLIVAN: Had you ever heard of a circumstance in which a letter
from a Cabinet officer to a congressman would be the basis for a
criminal charge?
   NORTH: No, these were political disputes. This was a political
battle the likes of which I guess Washington has a lot of them. It
was a nasty political dispute. It was politics at its worst but it
never occurred to me, I've never heard of it before or since until
this, that that kind of a thing could be unlawful. ... I mean my
argument (against responding to Barnes and Hamilton) wasn't based
on something being unlawful. My argument was based on the fact that
if there's ever a chance to use this kind of privilege, authority,
it ought to be used on this. ... it never occurred to me that it
was unlawful.
   SULLIVAN: The next thing that happens, let's go to June 1986.
What does the Congress do at that time with regard to a resolution
of inquiry? (The House resolution formally requested information on
North's activities.) What was the conclusion you drew (from this
resolution)?
   NORTH: Well, the conclusion I drew is this was just one more
chapter in this very bitter political dispute in which both sides
were pulling out all the stops. ... (Our response was) the fact
that we've answered these questions before, meaning Mr. McFarlane's
answers the year before. ...
   (North then discusses an informal meeting with Rep. Hamilton in
the White House situation room on Aug. 6, 1986.)
   SULLIVAN: What did that mean to you, informal? Off the record?
   NORTH: I guess my sense of it was that this was simply an effort
to stop the inquiries ....
   SULLIVAN: Did you ever think you would be in a courtroom some
day in 1989 being charged with a crime because of a meeting that
occurred on August 6th, 1986, which was off the record, informal?
   NORTH: No, sir.
   SULLIVAN: Did you tell them the truth at that meeting on August
6th, 1986?
   NORTH: No.
   SULLIVAN: When you didn't disclose information they were looking
at, did you believe that your conduct was unlawful?
   NORTH: No, I didn't think it was unlawful but I was raised to
know the difference between right and wrong. I knew it wasn't right
not to tell the truth on those things, but I didn't think it was
unlawful.
   SULLIVAN: How did you feel about being told by your boss to go
into a meeting on August 6th, 1986?
   NORTH: I felt like a pawn in a chess game being played by
giants. ... I had been told specifically that the Saudi aid that
the president had gotten and that Mr. McFarlane had gotten will
never be revealed. And by this time we were also using monies from
the sale of arms to the Nicaraguan resistance _ to the Iranians to
help the Nicaraguan resistance, and that would never be revealed.
   SULLIVAN: Was it your understanding that if you answered frankly
the questions that were asked in that session that it would lead to
being confronted with having to reveal some of those things?
   NORTH: Yes, and that's why I didn't think that that meeting was
a good idea.
   SULLIVAN: And did you tell Admiral Poindexter that?
   NORTH: I did.
   SULLIVAN: And what was his decision?
   NORTH: You can take care of it.
   (North describes exchanges in which his superior, Adm. John
Poindexter, McFarlane's successor as national security adviser,
discussed concerns that too many people were beginning to find out
what North is doing in Central America.)
   NORTH: He ... told me that I .... must generate a cover story;
just don't be letting people know where you are going, what you are
doing and why you are doing it. And so I did so.
   SULLIVAN: Now (Poindexter) speaks of ``operational roles'' ..
what did you understand it to mean?
   NORTH: Well, he specifically said to me, that goes for the
terrorism business, that goes for the hostage business, that goes
for all the reasons that you're doing with the resistance.
</TEXT>
