<FIRST>r a PM-RodeoBulls     04-08 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rodeo Bulls,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Supporters Say Bulls At Rodeo Will Be Exploited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ODESSA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal-rights activists say letting bulls
loose in an arena with rodeo clowns will exploit and mentally
torment the animals.
   ``It is morally, ethically and legally wrong to torment an
animal to the point where it's going to charge you,'' said Raini
Sequoya, president of the Tampa-based National Animal Rights Inc.
``If these clowns really want to have some fun, they should get in
the ring and torment each other. Why pick on a helpless animal?''
   But organizers of this weekend's Odessa Rodeo &amp; Yukon Days said
nothing is wrong with the crowd-pleasing event.
   ``I don't understand. Is waving a flag in a bull's face more
cruel than getting on his back and riding him?'' said organizer
John Burchell.
   Steve Fleming, spokesman for the Professional Rodeo Cowboy's
Association in Colorado, was taken aback by the criticism.
   ``This is great. ... A clown goes out and stands in the middle
of an arena and they let a bull out to chase him _ kind of like
turning a bulldog loose on a mailman _ and people are worried for
the bull,'' said Fleming.
   The event is for clowns to display their bravery and talent, he
said. The clowns have 70 seconds to show judges how they avoid
getting killed. They can't touch the bull or use weapons and have
only a barrel to crawl into.
   The activists had vowed to seek an injunction to stop the event
on the grounds that it breaks Florida's 88-year-old animal cruelty
law. But they had not done so by Friday, and were considering plans
to file legal action after the event.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
