<FIRST>r w PM-Flight103-Families     04-08 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Families,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Of Flight 103 Victims Lambast `Callousness' Of U.S. Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her voice trembling with pain and then anger,
Eleanor Bright recalled her late husband and lambasted what she
called the callousness of U.S. officials following the bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103.
   ``After suffering the unimaginable loss of my husband, I have
had to fight to get information. That's not right,'' said Mrs.
Bright, the mother of a 19-month-old son, echoing complaints from
other victims' family members.
   A Senate hearing room was hushed Friday, the only sound an
occasional muffled cry from other family members, as the
32-year-old widow from Brookline, Mass., told about the
difficulties of getting information from the State Department
following the Dec. 21 terrorist bombing over Scotland that claimed
270 victims.
   ``I call Washington, I call Scotland, and in anger and
frustration I call other victims,'' she told the Senate Foreign
Relations terrorism subcommittee.
   ``The stories never end,'' she said. ``Memorials unattended by
State Department officials. Someone told to come `pick up the
shipment' when her husband's body arrived from Scotland. Someone
else watched as the body of her loved one was lifted off a platform
using a forklift. One widow was told it was time to realize that
her husband was dead and get on with her life.''
   Mrs. Bright, unable to steady her voice, told a subcommittee
headed by John F. Kerry, D-Mass., of her own experiences _ how it
was nine hours after the accident before the airline called, how
the State Department did not call for days and how the only answers
at the accident scene in Lockerbie, Scotland, came from Scottish
officials.
   ``I learned through my husband's employer that Nicholas was
seated in seat 14A, directly over the bomb,'' she said. ``I need to
know what that meant. Was he ever aware of what was happening? Was
he ever afraid? Was he in pain?
   ``It was not until February that I learned by chance that an
autopsy had been performed on Nicholas. All of this information
should have given by the State Department or Pan Am, but it wasn't.
Why were they silent? Instead of me being allowed to grieve for the
loss of my husband, I was forced to seek out answers on my own.''
   ``As my husband so strongly believed, there is a right answer
and it's worth fighting for. The right answer is that we need a
responsive, informative and compassionate State Department,'' Mrs.
Bright said. ``It would not have taken a lot of manpower or dollars
to have dealt with this differently.''
   Assistant Secretary of State Joan M. Clark defended the
government's response, saying the State Department had planned to
contact next-of-kin, but Pan Am wanted to do it and the government
has ``no legal authority to compel an airline to give us a
passenger list.''
   ``Our objective was to spare (the families) as much anguish as
possible,'' she said. ``We refrained, however, from taking a more
active role with family members for fear of intruding unnecessarily
during that time of tragedy and shock.''
   But she conceded that the State Department has ``learned a great
deal from this experience'' and ``are reviewing our methods for
handling crises and are making appropriate changes.''
   She said the government is seeking an agreement with the major
airlines to coordinate emergency action plans. In addition, the
department has organized an 18-member special family liaison group
to provide one-on-one information for each family of the Flight 103
disaster and is considering an 800 telephone number in disaster
situations.
   Kerry joined the family members in calling for a new policy to
tell passengers about terrorist threats and to increase airport
security checks even if it means much longer waiting times for
passengers.
   Monte R. Belger, associate administrator at the Federal Aviation
Administration, said he believes new government regulations
mandating devices to detect plastic explosives and other changes
ordered in the wake of the Flight 103 disaster are sufficient.
</TEXT>
