<FIRST>r a PM-TankerFreed     04-08 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Freed,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Tanker Runs Aground On Mississippi River; No Oil Spilled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McKNIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerful currents and a channel that's tough
to negotiate may have been partly to blame for the grounding of an
Exxon tanker on a sandbar in the Mississippi River, a Coast Guard
official said.
   The 617-foot Exxon Wilmington, carrying 13 million gallons of
oil products, got stuck Friday on the muddy bottom near the mouth
of the Mississippi River. Four tugboats freed it after seven hours.
No oil spilled from the ship.
   ``Where the river's at now, it's tricky down there,'' said Capt.
John Klotz of the Coast Guard's district headquarters.
   Klotz said the river is rising and currents are powerful where
the ship went aground _ a point where the main channel splits into
three smaller channels emptying into the Gulf of Mexico.
   He said the river is 38 to 39 feet deep there, though the Army
Corps of Engineers tries to maintain a 45-foot depth.
   Klotz, who inspected the grounded Exxon Wilmington from a
helicopter, said checks of the ship's double hull indicated it was
undamaged.
   The Wilmington steamed Friday night to an anchorage in the Gulf
of Mexico where Coast Guard inspectors were to give its hull a
final check for damage before letting it proceed to a refinery at
Bayway, N.J.
   The Coast Guard is investigating why the Wilmington ran aground.
   The ship was loaded with more than 8 million gallons of jet fuel
and nearly 5 million gallons of other petroleum products, mainly
paraffin. It took on the cargo at the Exxon refinery at Baton
Rouge, said Exxon spokesman John Reidy.
   It was the second Exxon tanker to run aground. On March 24, the
Exxon Valdez struck a reef in Alaska's Prince William Sound and
spilled 10.1 million barrels of oil in the worst spill in U.S.
history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
