<DOCNO> AP890408-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev     04-08 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader Ends Goodwill Tour By Inviting Queen To Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev ended a
six-day tour of Ireland, Cuba and Britain by announcing nuclear
cutbacks and inviting Queen Elizabeth II to visit Moscow.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Friday that the queen gave
``a very definite yes,'' but that no date had been set.
   She would be the first British sovereign to visit the Soviet
Union since the 1917 revolution. Her Russian ancestors _ the family
of Czar Nicholas II _ were slain by revolutionaries eight decades
ago.
   Gorbachev's invitation to the queen indicated his success in
winning Mrs. Thatcher's trust. In addition, televised pictures of
the Gorbachevs being escorted around Windsor Castle by the
63-year-old queen and her husband, Prince Philip, further warmed
the royalty-loving British to the Soviet leader.
   Despite the invitation and the cordiality, Mrs. Thatcher and
Gorbachev disagreed on issues of nuclear disarmament and the
balance of East-West forces in Europe.
   Mrs. Thatcher, moreover, downplayed the importance of the Soviet
leader's promise to halt production of weapons-grade uranium and
shut down two more plutonium-producing reactors by the end of 1990.
   Nevertheless, she declared Gorbachev's third visit to Britain
``very successful, warm and friendly,'' echoing his assertion that
it had strengthened British-Soviet ties.
   The Gorbachevs' 40-hour British stay ended with a day steeped in
pageantry.
   The president gave an unusually brief, 27-minute speech in the
splendid setting of London's Guildhall, the 1,000-year-old seat of
city government filled with city leaders in wigs and robes.
   In remarks broadcast live in Britain and the United States,
Gorbachev called his proposals for cutting production of
radioactive material ``another major step toward the complete
cessation of production of fissionable materials for use in nuclear
weapons.''
   However, Mrs. Thatcher later ascribed little importance to the
moves, saying existing Soviet stockpiles would mean the cutbacks
``will have no effect in practice.'' A U.S. Defense Department
official said the weapons reactors could be started when the Soviet
military runs low.
   The Soviet step followed Gorbachev's December announcement to
the United Nations that the Soviet Union would soon cut 500,000
soldiers from its standing army and withdraw troops and tanks from
European and Chinese frontiers.
   Gorbachev lauded Britain for unilaterally eliminating chemical
weapons stocks. He said his country had built a facility for
destroying its own chemical weapons, and he would soon invite
British experts to inspect it.
   The president also said the West should drop plans to modernize
short-range nuclear missiles, but Mrs. Thatcher maintained a
nuclear deterrent was essential.
   After lunch at Windsor Castle, the Gorbachevs were driven to
London's Heathrow Airport, where they flew home to Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     04-08 0878</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0912</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRUM, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaimie Hogan only wanted a poster of Tom
Cruise, but the 8-year-old girl with muscular dystrophy got to have
lunch with the popular actor instead.
   Jaimie's date with the co-star of the Academy Award-winning
movie ``Rain Man'' was arranged by Make-A-Wish Foundation, a
charity that grants wishes of children ages 2{ to 18 who have
life-threatening illnesses.
   When applying to Make-A-Wish, Jaimie's mother, Jacque Hogan,
wrote that Jaimie saw Cruise's ``Top Gun'' 20 times and
``Cocktail,'' her favorite movie, twice.
   Jaimie, her parents and a friend flew to Los Angeles at the end
of March to meet Cruise.
   ``She was real shy around him ... she hardly looked at him,''
Mrs. Hogan said. ``The kids couldn't think of a thing to ask him.''
   Cruise talked about his newest movie, ``Born on the Fourth of
July,'' about a paraplegic Vietnam veteran, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of ``Blaze,'' a movie about
the late Gov. Earl Long and stripper Blaze Starr, says the film
will treat a legendary portion of Louisiana history with ``great
tenderness and affection.''
   Ron Shelton, who directed ``Bull Durham,'' says the movie
``features two American legends who had their roots in Louisiana.''
   Starr, a stripper with whom Long had a scandalous affair 30
years ago, is serving as a consultant to the film, which stars Paul
Newman as the colorful governor in his waning days of office.
   The movie's script came from historical research and interviews
with people who knew Long during the late 1950s and early '60s,
when the governor created controversy by backing social welfare
programs and voter rights, Shelton said.
   The movie, which begins filming Monday, is scheduled for
Christmas release in New York City and Los Angeles and general
distribution in early 1990.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson warned a crowd that ``war
will not work'' as he dedicated the Berkeley Peace Wall, two
concrete slabs featuring painted ceramic tiles.
   The wall, two 4-foot-tall semicircular concrete arcs in a patio
at Martin Luther King Jr. Park, was the brainchild of local artist
Carolyn Marks, who calls it a ``basic human family quilt.''
   The tiles came from more than a dozen countries, including the
Soviet Union, and carry slogans and artwork aimed at promoting
peace. One read, ``Peace through learning about each other.''
Another said, ``Humanity is one.''
   Some 2,000 people, from preschoolers to one elderly woman
wearing a Gray Panthers button, gathered Friday under a bright blue
sky in unseasonably warm weather to view the wall.
   Jackson compared the peace wall to the wall that separates East
and West Berlin, saying: ``I look forward to the day when we can
put tiles on the wall in Berlin.
   ``Our generation must be intelligent enough to give peace a
chance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk isn't cheap when it comes to baseball
announcer Bob Uecker, former Gov. Lee Dreyfus and NBC basketball
announcer Al McGuire, who have turned their silver tongues to gold
by speaking their pieces for a price.
   A newspaper study found the going rates are $25,000 for Uecker,
$7,000 for Dreyfus and $5,000 for McGuire.
   Uecker has little time for speaking these days, especially after
suffering a mild heart atack in February. But when he does have
time to squeeze in an appearance between taping his ``Mr.
Belvedere'' television show and broadcasting Milwaukee Brewers
games, his appearance fee puts him in the range of such celebrities
as talk-show host Oprah Winfrey and former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
   Dreyfus, a Republican, left the governor's officer six year ago
and his career as a lecturer has built steadily since then.
   McGuire, the former Marquette University coach, is especially in
demand in the Southeast, according to his assistant, Jeannine
McKeown. ``It's a basketball hotbed down there,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phoenix Suns radio announcer Al McCoy was the
iron man of the mike for 17 years, but his consecutive-game string
has ended at 1,463.
   McCoy, the voice of the National Basketball Association,
contracted laryngitis after broadcasting Phoenix's 114-104 win over
Utah Wednesday night.
   He attended Thursday night's game at Seattle, but producer Greg
Schulte of radio station KTAR in Phoenix handled the play-by-play.
It was the first time in 17 years that McCoy did not do the
broadcast.
   Suns officials said they are not sure if McCoy can recover in
time to do tonight's game against the Los Angeles Clippers and
start another streak.
