<TEXT>
   The Grateful Dead concert scheduled tonight
will have beefed-up police presence because of violence at concerts
in Pittsburgh earlier this week.
   Thirty-three officers will be at Riverfront Coliseum, with 82
security officers and 60 ushers, said Dave Rager, the city's
assistant safety director.
   Most of the 16,144 tickets sold went to out-of-towners, with
almost 7,000 going to ``Dead Heads,'' as the group's ardent fans
are called. They often camp out at concerts and trade tapes and
souvenirs.
   Police in Pittsburgh arrested 55 people, mostly on public
intoxication and drug charges, at Grateful Dead concerts Sunday and
Monday. Pittsburgh police clashed Monday night with a crowd of more
than 500 who had surrounded the Civic Arena but did not have
concert tickets.
