<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearLicensing     04-08 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Licensing,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Streamlining of Nuclear Licensing Adopted by NRC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission hopes its
streamlining of the nuclear licensing process will keep the
industry alive by cutting the time needed to build a nuclear power
plant by roughly half.
   The new licensing procedures, approved by the five-member
commission without dissent on Friday, have been under development
for more than two years and have been the subject of hearings and
briefings.
   The commission staff, utility executives and other analysts have
said that there was no chance anyone would ever build another plant
without some licensing simplification, although there is no sign
that any utilities are close to seeking approval.
   The procedures try to resolve all major issues before a decision
on whether to go ahead with a plant. They provide for advance
approval of plant designs that could be used with little further
examination, and of sites that utilities could designate far in
advance of need.
   Also, the commission would go a long way toward the
much-discussed ``one-stop'' license, issuing a combined
construction permit and operating license.
   License applicants could still use the old procedure but the
commission does not expect anyone to do so.
   Site approval would be good for 20 years.
   Without new legislation, which the commission has been unable to
win, the procedure cannot be completely one-stop. Under current
law, the commission still will have to hold both a licensing
hearing and a hearing after a plant has been built before it can be
started.
   The new combined license would be issued only after safety and
site issues such as planning for emergency evacuations had been
resolved. The range of issues that could be raised at the second
hearing on whether license conditions had been met would be
narrowed, and Commission Chairman Lando Zech told reporters he did
not think legislation was necessary now.
   At the second hearing, issues would be limited to allegations of
``material and uncorrected non-conformance'' with license
conditions, or that ``adequate protection'' of the public is in
jeopardy.
   Failure of state and local governments to cooperate in emergency
planning has held up licensing of the completed Shoreham plant on
Long Island and the Seabrook plant on the New Hampshire coast.
   Under the new procedure, an applicant would have to show a
``good faith'' effort to win such cooperation in evacuation
planning and that the plan could work even without it.
   These issues are not even considered under the current procedure
until the plant is finished and the question before the commission
is whether to allow operation.
   Huge cost escalations, a drastic slowing of growth in
electricity demand in the past decade and fears generated by the
partial core melt of the Three Mile Island plant in Pennsylvania in
1979 and other accidents combined years ago to kill new orders for
an industry that provides 18 percent of the nation's electricity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
