<FIRST>u i AM-Norway-SovietSub 3rdLd-Writethru   04-08 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Soviet Sub, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0430,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Embassy Confirms Nuclear Sub Sank Off Northern Norway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with oil slick, Russian vessels
at scene. Picks up graf 12 pvs, `It was ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Sub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Embassy confirmed that a
nuclear-powered submarine suffered an underwater accident and sank
in international waters off northern Norway, according to a radio
report Saturday.
   Defense Minister Johan Juergen Holst said on Norwegian Radio
that estimates of about 12 fatalities from the sinking Friday of
the Soviet ``Mike'' class submarine appeared accurate. Some crewmen
apparently were rescued, Holst said but he provided no details.
   A Norwegian Orion reconnaissance plane saw Soviet ships and
planes circling the accident site north of the Arctic Circle before
nightfall Friday. A second Orion passed over the area after
midnight and spotted an oil slick on the sea, Holst said.
   He said a Soviet cruiser was en route to the scene, and that
Norwegian vessels had made no attempts to approach the site, 118
miles south-southwest of Bear Island in the Norwegian Sea and 312
miles off Norway.
   Norwegian experts were meeting Saturday morning to discuss the
situation and keep the government informed about the possibility of
a radiation leak, the broadcast said.
   By Saturday, more than 12 hours after the accident, there was no
word on the accident from the Soviet government or the official
Tass news agency.
   The sea is 6,600 feet deep at the site of the sinking, and Holst
said there was ``no hope'' of raising the sub from the bottom.
Military officials in Norway and Washington said it appeared the
boat caught fire underwater before breaking up and sinking.
   The submarine, nicknamed ``Mike'' by the United States and NATO,
carries a crew of 95, is powered by two nuclear generators and is
reportedly equipped with torpedoes and long-range ballistic
missiles, Western sources say.
   The West German government radio also quoted Holst as saying
pilots of reconnaissance planes reported seeing bodies at the site.
   U.S. officials said there ``definitely'' were casualties aboard,
but declined to estimate how many.
   ``The only thing we saw was an oil slick about three to four
hundred meters long by 50 to 100 meters wide,'' Capt. Haavard Holm,
the Orion reconnaissance pilot, said on Norwegian Radio after
flying over the accident site.
   He said there were three Russian ships and one aircraft in the
area, including a trawler, a freezer ship and what appeared to be
an observation or intelligence vessel.
   Holst said he doubted the Soviets had sent the cruiser to keep
other ships away.
   ``They want to have as much support as possible and want to
transfer the survivors and the possible dead,'' he said.
   Defense Ministry officials said earlier that the reconnaissance
plane had seen Soviet planes and boats, including rubber dinghies
with people in at least one of them.
   It was not clear whether the people were from the submarine or
the surface vessels.
   ``With the observations we have made with the Soviet vessels and
planes in the area, it seems the Soviets can handle this case
alone,'' Holst said.
   The area is well above the Arctic Circle, but is usually
ice-free because of the Gulf Stream. Temperatures in the area were
near-freezing on Friday.
   The ``Mike'' is one of the Soviet Union's modern submarines, and
the only one in operation, according to Jane's Fighting Ships, the
British reference book.
   If Western descriptions of the submarine are accurate, ``the
reactors are well-protected and have less radioactive material than
in older submarines.'' said Johan Baarli, director of Norway's
Institute for Radiation Protection.
   He said on national radio that any radioactive material probably
would remain in the sub and not escape into the sea.
   Norwegian and Swedish defense sources estimate the Soviet Union
has about 110 nuclear submarines operating in northern waters from
bases on the Kola Peninsula, one of the world's heaviest
concentrations of naval power.
   The ``Mike'' might carry 16 missiles for surface targets,
although the figure is unconfirmed, said Swedish Defense Ministry
spokesman Thomas Gur.
</TEXT>
