<FIRST>r w PM-DC-DrugWar     04-08 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Drug War,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Prepares Massive Effort Against Drugs in Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration plans to construct a
new federal penitentiary in the Washington suburbs and a temporary
jail in the city to help fight the District of Columbia's drug and
violent crime problem.
   The New York Times and The Washington Post reported in their
editions today that national drug control policy director William
J. Bennett will announce his plans Monday.
   The reports, citing unidentified sources, said the plan will
call for National Guard troops to perform clerical jobs to free up
police officers, and an enhanced role for federal law enforcement
agents in the city's anti-drug efforts.
   Bennett's deputy chief of staff, David Tell, said late Friday
that he could not comment on the reports.
   Bennett has targeted the nation's capital, where an epidemic
drug-related killings have earned the city the title of ``murder
capital,'' in his national campaign against drugs.
   The Post reported that the wide-ranging federal effort will
include the use of forensic experts at the FBI to help reduce the
mounting backlog of unsolved homicide cases, and Drug Enforcement
Administration funds will be used to pay for police overtime.
   In addition, a DEA local task force will be expanded, with more
than a dozen supervisory DEA agents brought in to help local police
officials manage major drug cases, and five intelligence analysts
from the Defense Department will be detailed to help track drug
dealing.
   There have been 132 homicides, most of them drug-related, in the
district this year compared with 87 at the same time in 1988, when
the city had a record 372 murders.
   Among the plans outlined by the officials, according to the
newspapers, were these:
   _A new prison would be built to relieve overcrowding at a
6,000-inmate facility, the district-operated Lorton Reformatory
prison complex in suburban Virginia, beginning in fiscal year 1991.
   _About 200 to 300 prisoners would be transferred temporarily
from Lorton to federal prisons around the country. Such transfers
have occurred in the past because of the overcrowding.
   _A contingent from the U.S. Marshals Service would be assigned
to the city to make evictions in the estimated 200 to 300 crack
houses that thrive here, and to help the local police apprehend
suspects on outstanding warrants.
   _The Defense Department will use intelligence officials to
analyze international drug trafficking.
   _The DEA has agreed to assign about 15 officials temporarily to
Washington to double an existing task force that coordinates
efforts by regional police departments to pursue drug offenders.
   An administration official familiar with the plan told the Post
that Fort Meade, an Army post near Annapolis, Md., which houses the
National Security Agency and various military facilities, ``is one
of the options'' under study for the new federal penitentiary but
that no final decision has been made.
</TEXT>
