<FIRST>u w BC-NorthTrial-Testimony 5thAdd   04-08 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Trial-Testimony, 5th Add,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: coming out.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SULLIVAN: What was the danger in revealing the Iranian
initiative in terms of the second channel and the hostages?
   NORTH: Well, the danger that we all saw was that you'd end up
with the political fire storm we ended up with, I mean that
actually happened, that you'd end up with exposure of the kind that
even though officials within the Iranian government knew what was
going on and officials within our government knew what was going
on, that neither the Iranian public nor the American public were
going to be particularly happy with this. (And) ... that the people
in Lebanon who held the hostages would be so outraged by this
involvement.
   SULLIVAN: Was there a time when it was thought that there would
be a cover story that would have to be used in order to protect the
Iranian initiative?
   NORTH: There was a cover story. There had been a cover story _
   SULLIVAN: Describe what you mean?
   NORTH: There had been a cover story since February of 1986 when
we started to get the Hawk missiles back out of Iran. We told the
Iranians because they were so upset with that Israeli shipment that
we had nothing to do with it ...
   (North describes a number of ``chronologies'' that were being
developed by the CIA, Poindexter and McFarlane in connection with
the Iranian initiatives.)
   SULLIVAN: What was your understanding of what the president was
saying publicly about these matters?
   NORTH: Well, the president had publicly said that they didn't
happen either, which was initially part of the cover story.
   SULLIVAN: What conclusion did you draw from that?
   NORTH: ... I had no idea what was in the minds of other people
but it was very clear to me that the president himself out publicly
on a number of occasions ... and people were digging a pretty deep
hole, without me helping them, in advancing (the cover) story.
</TEXT>
