<DOCNO> AP890408-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill Bjt   04-08 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Storm Calmed, Officials Now Worrying About Shifting Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews tackling the worst oil spill in U.S.
history got good news from Washington on who's in charge of the
cleanup and bad news from a weather forecast that could put
untainted shoreline in jeopardy.
   Only 7 percent of the 10.1 million gallons of oil has been
retrieved.
   President Bush announced Friday he was sending military troops
to help clean up the oil that leaked from tanker Exxon Valdez on
March 24.
   Bush said the Coast Guard was taking control of the operation,
ending days of bickering and weeks of frustration over the oil
company's efforts.
   ``I think we had a problem with organization _ that's what
frustrated everybody,'' said Rear Adm. Edward Nelson Jr., the
commander of the Coast Guard's Alaskan district who now heads the
cleanup operation. ``We now see a clean line of what's going to go
on.''
   Under the new plan, reached by compromise at the request of
Alaskan officials, the Coast Guard will have final responsibility
for running the cleanup effort. Exxon will continue to provide the
materials and manpower and will not be relieved of liability.
   ``We'll be directing the strategic application of forces. ...
Exxon retains the role of support,'' said Nelson.
   The change in command came as weather forecasters warned of a
change in the winds that have pushed nearly half the oil south and
out of the environmentally sensitive Prince William Sound in the
two weeks since the tanker ran aground on Bligh Reef.
   The shift in direction threatens to push oil slicks, which have
already traveled over a 3,000-square-mile area in the Gulf of
Alaska, toward Kodiak Island and the fragile bays and inlets of the
Kenai Peninsula.
   So far, only an estimated 16,000 barrels of oil have been sopped
and vacuumed up from the once-clear water of Prince William Sound.
The spill has killed thousands of birds and sea otters along the
central Alaskan coast, cost fishermen millions of dollars in lost
catch and continues to threaten valuable salmon fisheries.
   A shift in the wind ``could easily double the area affected,''
said Jim Hayden, coordinator of the state's cleanup effort.
   A large oil slick continued to threaten the edges of Kenai
Fjords National Park, a remote refuge 100 miles southwest of
Valdez, as workers set up floating oil booms to protected against
the expected onslaught.
   ``We're preparing for the worse case,'' said John Quinley, a
spokesman for the National Park Service. ``Even if this doesn't
foul the beaches this stuff could be there for a long time.''
   Bush said at a news conference in Washington that he was
directing Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to make military forces and
equipment available. He also directed Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner to coordinate the effort.
   Bush had been under pressure from members of Congress and
Alaskan officials to intervene. Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper on
Wednesday asked the Coast Guard to take over management of the
cleanup from Exxon.
   The president insisted, however, ``We are not federalizing this
operation,'' and that ``this should not relieve Exxon from any of
its responsibilities or liabilities.''
   State officials said they were pleased with Bush's decision but
worried that the use of military troops in the cleaup might disrupt
the effort and deny jobs to state residents.
   But Nelson said he didn't anticipate the wholesale use of troops.
   ``We have a plan and we want to proceed rather cautiously,'' he
said. ``What we're really going to do is have local hire.''
   Cowper said he was pleased with Bush's action, although he
agrees that Alaskans should get available work before the military.
   ``It appears the president is meeting the objectives we had in
asking the Coast Guard to take over the spill cleanup in Prince
William Sound,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
