<DOCNO> AP890408-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0504EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-08 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elementary school principal Steve Hall may
hedge his bets in the future.
   He lost a wager with the Albany Elementary's 275 students that
they could not collectively read 1 million pages of books or
magazine articles by April 21.
   His penalty: a day on the school roof.
   Hall set up a desk with a telephone on the roof Friday and
received notes and messages by rope and bucket under cloudy skies
and in temperatures in the 40s. He had several visitors; many
carried cameras.
   The students, monitored by teachers and parents, made good on
the bet by Feb. 27. On the average, each student read about 4,500
pages, Hall said. Medals were awarded to those who read more than
3,000 pages.
   Hall said he wanted to motivate the students to read, but he
didn't think they would complete the task.
   ``We're proud of them, it was a good effort,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judy McMillan celebrated her election to the
village board. The only downside was that she beat her mother.
   ``I feel great about winning,'' Mrs. McMillan said. ``I'm sorry
mom didn't make it, too, but I know she'll be supporting me all the
time.''
   Mrs. McMillan and her mother, Carrie Edgeton, were two of the
four candidates for the three-member Dana Village Board. Mrs.
Edgeton finished last with 34 votes, only six votes behind her
daughter in Tuesday's election.
   The two women ran on similar platforms: a desire for civic
improvements that would spruce up the north central Illinois town
of 250 people.
   The mother is not a sore loser. She noted her daughter entered
the race first.
   ``We've lived here since 1957,'' Mrs. Edgeton said, ``and I
don't remember a woman ever being on the board. We kidded Judy that
she should run. I just sort of got interested along the way and
decided a lot later that I'd run, too.''
   Mrs. McMillan said her mother will keep a close eye on the board.
   ``Mom will probably be at a lot of the meetings, so she'll be
keeping up with things and lending her support.''
</TEXT>
