<FIRST>r a PM-Maid-Fortune     04-08 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maid-Fortune,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Maid Accused Of Stealing Widow's Fortune</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former live-in maid has been charged with
stealing more than $880,000 from a paraplegic widow while keeping
the elderly woman a prisoner in her own home.
   Barbara Stevens, 54, confined Valeria Lust to her Lakeland home
by giving her incapacitating drugs and taking away the 71-year-old
woman's walker and telephone, according to court documents.
   While living with the widow for a year until January 1988, Ms.
Stevens forged her name on 20 checks worth $883,534 and gave some
of the money to a North Carolina-based television ministry,
according to an affidavit filed Thursday.
   In a separate civil case, Mrs. Lust claims more than $700,000 of
her money went to the Fountain of Life Inc. ministry.
   Jim Whittington, president of Fountain of Life, confirmed the
ministry received about $700,000 from Mrs. Lust, and said the money
was a donation.
   Ms. Stevens, who was arrested Thursday, was charged with 20
counts of grand theft, 21 counts of forgery, 20 counts of uttering
a forged instrument and false imprisonment.
   She was ordered held in the Polk County Jail in lieu of $500,000
bail.
   In June, Mrs. Lust's attorneys sued the ministry, claiming Ms.
Stevens used undue influence to get her to donate more than
$700,000, court records state.
   Although $711,941 allegedly was deposited in a North Carolina
account set up in the names of Ms. Stevens and Mrs. Lust, the widow
told authorities she knew of no such account.
   The civil lawsuit between Mrs. Lust and Fountain of Life is
pending. No criminal trial date has been set.
   Melonie Milling, Ms. Stevens' 27-year-old daughter, also lived
in Mrs. Lust's home, investigators said.
   Ms. Stevens illegally obtained prescription drugs and gave them
to Mrs. Lust to keep her sleepy so she would not complain, Ms.
Milling told authorities.
   Ms. Milling also said her mother disconnected the telephone in
the woman's bedroom and told her: ``See, no one cares, no one
calls; your children don't even call.''
   Mrs. Lust, a paraplegic since suffering a stroke in 1982, also
has impaired vision as a result of unsuccessful cataract surgery.
</TEXT>
