<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     04-08 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Police Close MacDonald's Office; Violence Mars Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navajo police enforced a court order
barring embattled Chairman Peter MacDonald from his offices at the
nation's largest Indian tribe, and minor violence marred an
anti-MacDonald rally.
   MacDonald did not show up for work Friday, and his staff was out
of the administration building by the time the tribal officers
closed the offices.
   About 750 people turned up for a demonstration stemming from the
Tribal Council's 49-13 vote on Feb. 17 to place MacDonald and Vice
Chairman Johnny R. Thompson on administrative leave.
   MacDonald, who has been accused in U.S. Senate testimony of
receiving gifts and kickbacks in connection with tribal business
dealings, had offered to step down temporarily but recanted when
the tribe refused to pay his anticipated defense costs.
   Tribal business conducted since MacDonald was re-elected in 1986
reportedly is the subject of a probe by a federal grand jury in
Phoenix.
   MacDonald publicly has denied any wrongdoing, but he has refused
to discuss the allegations against him with reporters.
   Spokesman Ferlin Clark said Friday that MacDonald would have no
comment on the latest developments.
   At the demonstration, tribal police arrested two anti-MacDonald
demonstrators, used tear gas on the crowd and threatened to turn
fire hoses on others. No injuries were reported.
   A tribal police sergeant, who refused to give his name, said the
two arrests at the demonstration occurred after a fight and an
assault on a MacDonald bodyguard.
   The Navajo Reservation, home to the nation's largest Indian
tribe, includes parts of northeastern Arizona, northwestern New
Mexico and southeastern Utah.
</TEXT>
