<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Malaysia-Frogs     04-08 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia-Frogs,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Frog Found In Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zoologists at the University of
Malaya said today they have found a frog that grows out of an egg
instead of going through the tadpole stage in water.
   Zoology professor Yong Hoi Sen said he and a team of colleagues
discovered a tree frog, philautus aurifasciatus, which can breed on
land without water, while on a jungle expedition last February in
the Genting Highlands area about 20 miles east of Kuala Lumpur.
   He said the eggs were found on a pitcher plant, and were the
first time such a frog had been found in Malaysia.
   Most frogs lay eggs in water that become tadpoles, which mature
into frogs and leave the water. Yong said the tree frog the
zoologists discovered lays its eggs on land and that the eggs hatch
frogs.
   He said news of the discovery was withheld to carry out breeding
and tests.
   The frog is one of 17 species found on Malaysian trees. There
are 70 species of frogs in Malaysia.
   The philautus aurifasciatus also has been found in South America
and Australia and are known to exist in Thailand, Cambodia,
Indonesia and the Philippines, Yong said.
</TEXT>
