<DOCNO> AP890408-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Submarine-Accidents     04-08 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Submarine-Accidents,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Have Died in Accidents Aboard Nuclear Submarines Since 1954</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Sub, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of U.S. and Soviet crew members have died in accidents
involving nuclear-powered submarines since the first, the USS
Nautilus, was launched in 1954. Here is a list of accidents which
have been disclosed to the public:
   Oct. 3, 1986: A Soviet Yankee-class submarine, powered by two
nuclear reactors and carrying up to 16 nuclear-tipped missiles, was
wracked by fire and an explosion while cruising submerged about
1,000 miles off the North Carolina coast. The Soviets said three
sailors died in the fire and explosion, but the rest of the crew
was rescued before the sub sank to the ocean floor Oct. 6.
   April 29, 1986: The U.S. attack submarine Atlanta ran aground
while passing through the Straits of Gibraltar. The Navy said there
were no injuries, no damage to the nuclear propulsion system and
that the sub went to Gibraltar under its own power.
   April 1, 1986: The USS Nathaniel Green, armed with
nuclear-tipped Poseidon missiles, ran aground in the Irish Sea.
Although no major injuries were reported, the damage forced the
Navy to scrap the vessel.
   March 21, 1984: A Soviet submarine collided with the U.S.
aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk off Japan. No injuries were reported.
   Sept. 27, 1984: The USS Sam Rayburn, a Poseidon submarine,
collided with barrels containing nuclear waste off the British
coast, according to an anti-nuclear group.
   Sept. 21, 1984: The USS Jacksonville, an attack submarine,
collided with a Navy barge, causing superficial damage to the sub.
   Sept. 20, 1984: A Soviet Golf II class ballistic missile
submarine is spotted drifting in the Sea of Japan, with white smoke
pouring from its stern. The submarine later was reported to have
returned to its base in Vladivostok under its own steam.
   Dec. 23, 1983: The Navy said the USS Florida, a Poseidon
submarine, hit a submerged object during sea trials but was not
damaged.
   Summer 1983: A Soviet submarine sank in the northern Pacific,
killing 90 crew members, according to U.S. intelligence officials.
   Dec. 16, 1982: Two U.S. submarines, the La Jolla and the Permit,
collided during sea trials off San Diego but suffered only minor
damage.
   Nov. 30, 1982: The USS Thomas Edison collided with a Navy
destroyer in the South China Sea. No injuries were reported.
   March 24, 1982: The Jacksonville suffered $2 million in damage
in a collision with a Turkish freighter off the Virginia coast.
Both were able to continue under their own power.
   April 9, 1981: The USS George Washington, a missile submarine,
ran into the Japanese freighter Nisso Maru, sinking the surface
vessel off the southern tip of Japan, and killing two crewmen from
the Japanese ship.
   Oct. 27, 1981: A Soviet Whiskey-class diesel-powered submarine
ran aground in a restricted military zone in Sweden.
   Aug. 23, 1980: A Soviet Echo-1-class nuclear submarine caught
fire and radioed for help off Japan. Japanese officials later
reported that nine crew men died and three were injured in what
remains a mysterious accident.
   Feb. 5, 1977: The USS Snook collided with a sonar device being
towed by a Navy ship, damaging the submarine's periscope and
superstructure. No one was injured and there were no radiation
leaks, officials said.
   May 21, 1968: The USS Scorpion, an attack submarine, was lost
with 99 men aboard off the Azores in the Atlantic.
   1968: A Soviet submarine sank off the Kola Peninsula in the
Arctic Sea, according to recently declassified CIA documents.
   1968: A Soviet submarine sank in the Pacific, and subsequent
U.S. attempts to recover the wreck were partially successful.
   April 10, 1963: The USS Thresher was lost 220 miles off the New
England coast with all 129 men aboard; an investigation found that
the sub had gone into sea tests without adequate safety precautions.
   1961: Members of a Soviet submarine crew died of radiation
poisoning after an accident in the Baltic, according to recently
declassified CIA documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Visitor-AIDS     04-08 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Visitor-AIDS,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed Dutch AIDS Patient Arrives For Conference On Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with AIDS arrived from the
Netherlands after six days in a Minnesota prison and a battle with
immigration officials who refused to let him attend a U.S.
conference on the disease because of his illness.
   Hans Paul Verhoef, who was required by an immigration judge to
post a $10,000 bond, was given a bouquet of flowers by
representatives of the National Lesbian and Gay Health Conference
upon his arrival Friday night.
   Verhoef, who was detained by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service on Sunday at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International
Airport, declined to answer questions, saying he was very tired.
   A news conference with the 31-year-old AIDS worker was planned
today.
   ``We're very happy to have him finally here in San Francisco,''
said Scott Schafer, an aide to the mayor.
   A dozen or so supporters greeted Verhoef at the airport.
   ``I came because I think it's taken tremendous courage to take
on the great, big United States of America when you're just a
foreign visitor trying to help the world fight a terrible
disease,'' said Jennifer Maher.
   Verhoef flew into San Francisco just hours after a judge
overrode immigration officials and ordered him freed from the Oak
Park Heights State Prison so he could attend the conference.
   Immigration Judge Robert Vinikoor ruled Friday that Verhoef had
met standards allowing him to be excluded from laws barring
foreigners with dangerous and communicable diseases from entering
the country.
   Vinikoor's decision overrode INS officials in Washington who
denied Verhoef's request for a waiver to attend the AIDS conference.
   The INS then asked the federal Board of Immigration Appeals in
Falls Church, Va., to stay the judge's order. But Friday night the
board refused to consider the request.
   Vinikoor ordered Verhoef to post a $10,000 bond to enforce the
terms of the waiver, effective until April 28. The money was
provided by Minnesota AIDS Project, said Helene Haapala, one of
Verhoef's lawyers.
   ``I'm very disappointed being imprisoned and getting this
treatment in this country,'' Verhoef said before boarding the
flight to San Francisco.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, mostly between
homosexual males; needles or syringes shared by drug abusers;
infected blood or blood products; and from pregnant women to their
offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-China-Dissident     04-08 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dissident,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Dissident Arrives in United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese dissident put on a plane out of
the country by his government said his future is in limbo after he
arrived in the United States with $100 in his pocket.
   ``I cannot say I have been expelled. I do not know if I can go
back,'' Chen Jun told about three dozen reporters after he landed
at San Francisco International Airport on Friday evening.
   Chen, a 31-year-old Beijing bar owner, organized a petition in
February calling for immediate amnesty for political prisoners in
China. He was taken into custody Wednesday by government officials,
who said they needed to question him about possible parole
violations for a money changing conviction.
   He left Friday night for New York, where friends offered to give
him a place to stay.
   Although he declined to characterize himself as having been
expelled, he said he was ``was left no choice about whether to
leave or stay.''
   Earlier Friday, officials in Hong Kong had refused to let Chen
enter the colony, the dissident's British wife, Jenny Holdaway,
told reporters in Beijing.
   Chen boarded a Singapore Airlines jet for San Francisco when
Hong Kong officials refused to let him out of the Hong Kong airport
transit area.
   He arrived there Friday after Shanghai police, who had been
holding him for more than 36 hours, put him on a plane out of
China, she said. A Shanghai government official said he did not
know if Chen would be allowed to return.
   Several of those greeting Chen in San Francisco carried signs
with slogans reading, ``It is time to change China's destiny. The
only way to save China is democracy.''
   Huang Chuen Yu, chairman of the Chinese Democratic Education
Foundation, called the Chinese government's actions a ``very bad,
serious setback for the democratic reform movement under way.''
   An official at the Shanghai Foreign Affairs Office, who would
identify himself only as Mr. Fu, said Chen left the country
voluntarily.
   Chen had no Hong Kong visa but has a U.S. green card that gives
him residency rights. He lived in the United States from 1984 to
1987 and was married part of that time to an American woman.
   Ms. Holdaway said Chen and his father, He Weidu, were taken into
police custody Wednesday when they arrived in Shanghai from
Beijing. The father was released that night.
   Chen was kept in custody until he was put on the plane, and
other family members in Shanghai were refused permission to see
him, Ms. Holdaway said. He was allowed to call her just before
leaving.
   She said Chen had hoped to leave for the United States in a few
weeks for a prolonged stay and went to Shanghai to ask officials to
return his passport, which was confiscated last year.
   Last year, Chen was arrested in Shanghai, his hometown, for
changing U.S. dollars on the black market. Chen admitted to
changing money and agreed to pay a $5,300 fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
