<HEAD>Rain, Snow Across Midwest; Temperatures To Dip Under 100 In California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow fell on much of the Midwest today, adding to
flooding problems in North Dakota and Minnesota. In Southern
California, the forecast called for more heat, but highs were
expected to cool to below 100 degrees.
   Rain fell from western sections of the lower Ohio Valley across
the middle Mississippi Valley to the lower Missouri Valley,
changing to snow across parts of southern and eastern Minnesota and
northern Iowa. Two inches of snow fell at Mason City, Iowa, Poplar
Lake, Minn., and Estherville, Iowa, on Friday night.
   Flooding continued along the Red River in eastern North Dakota
as runoff has resulted in significant rises in the river. The
potential for ice jams remained great and rapid fluctuations of 1
to 3 feet were possible.
   A flood warning remained in effect for the Kennebec River in
Maine. The river was forecast to crest at 4 feet above flood stage
at Augusta, Maine, this morning before slowly receding.
   Rain fell over the mid-Atlantic Coast and southern New England.
Gusty winds also accompanied the low pressure system and gale
warnings were in effect along the coast from Maine to North
Carolina.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EST
included around 1 inch at Dover, Del., and three-quarters of an
inch at Millville, N.J.
   Strong winds howled across the higher elevations of the Colorado
Rockies, with gusts in excess of 70 mph at Rollinsville. North
winds gusted to 52 mph at Gage, Okla.
   Friday brought another day of record heat as downtown Los
Angeles had a high of 100 degrees, breaking the date's record of 88
set in 1904 and tied in 1962. The city reached a record-tying 100
on Tuesday and had record highs of 105 Wednesday and 106 Thursday.
   Record highs for the month were set at Ely, Nev., Phoenix, San
Francisco and San Jose, Calif.
   In contrast, a frost and freeze warning was in effect for parts
of the mountains and foothills of North Carolina.
   The high for the nation Friday was 112 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
across the Tennessee Valley, the central Gulf Coast states and
western North Carolina; rain from Virginia to New York; snow,
sometimes mixed with rain, in the Great Lakes region, the upper
Ohio Valley, the northern and central Appalachians, New England,
Wyoming and northern Colorado; snow in Montana and western South
Dakota; and gusty northerly winds in the upper and middle
Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were expected in the 30s and 40s from Montana
across the northern half of the Plains and Mississippi Valley, the
Great Lakes region and much of the Ohio Valley to New England; in
the 70s and 80s from southwest Oregon across Nevada, and much of
Texas to parts of Louisiana; in the 70s from Mississippi to
Florida; and in the 90s from California across southern Arizona and
southern New Mexico to southwest Texas, with 100- to 108-degree
readings in the deserts of southwest Arizona and southeast
California. Much of the rest of the nation was expected to have
highs in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m EDT ranged from 11
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 90 at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 partly cloudy; Boston 39 rain; Buffalo 28
fair; Charleston, S.C., 44 fair; Cincinnati 40 cloudy; Cleveland 31
fair; Detroit 35 fair; Miami 62 fair; New York 40 rain;
Philadelphia 42 rain; Pittsburgh 31 fair; Washington 43 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 27 fair; Chicago 37 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
72 fair; Denver 43 fair; Des Moines 35 drizzle; Indianapolis 41
rain; Kansas City 49 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 33 snow; Nashville
46 partly cloudy; New Orleans 66 foggy; St. Louis 45 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 56 fair; Anchorage 30 fair; Las Vegas 76
fair; Los Angeles 69 fair; Phoenix 82 fair; Salt Lake City 55 fair;
San Diego 70 fair; San Francisco 66 fair; Seattle 49 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 partly cloudy; Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
