<FIRST>u i PM-Cholesterol-Cancer     04-08 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cholesterol-Cancer,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Links Low Cholesterol in Some Men to Greater Cancer Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new medical study says a low-fat diet may not be
healthy for everyone and that a 12-year survey shows low
cholesterol levels coincide with an increased risk of cancer in
some men.
   The researchers reported in the weekly British Medical Journal,
published Friday, that their results also show people with high
cholesterol have a greater chance of getting heart disease. That
finding has been confirmed by other scientific teams and gained
widespread public acceptance.
   However, the latest team of researchers said their results also
show that low cholesterol levels sometimes coincide with a greater
risk from cancer, although this link was only significant for men.
   They said they could not explain why these people are more at
risk from cancer. They said the lower cholesterol itself could be
the culprit, but that something else may be the cause instead.
   The study is not the first to find a link between lower
cholesterol and higher cancer risk. Some researchers have suggested
lower cholesterol levels are in fact the product of undiagnosed
bowel cancers, because developing tumors trap cholesterol and
remove it from blood.
   While the issue remains unsettled, many other scientists doubt
high cholesterol levels help prevent cancer.
   The report said the survey was conducted among 15,262 people _
7,000 men and 8,262 women aged 45 to 64 in industrial southwestern
Scotland.
   The scientists said they found the most convincing link for lung
cancer. ``The inverse association between cholesterol concentration
and cancer in men was strongest for lung cancer.''
   The research team was comprised Victor M. Hawthorne of the
University of Michigan in Ann Arbor; Christopher G. Isles and
Anthony F. Lever, both of the blood pressure unit at the Western
Infirmary at Glasgow in southwest Scotland; and Charles R. Gillis
and David J. Hole, both of the cancer surveillance unit at
Glasgow's Ruchill Hospital.
   The team said more research is needed in the area.
   But, it added, ``We conclude that it may be a mistake to assume
that dietary advice given to the general population to reduce the
intake of saturated fat will necessarily reduce overall mortality.''
   Low-fat diets help reduce cholesterol. The team said such diets
are probably a good idea for people with high cholesterol levels.
   Their advice, however, was contradicted by Michael O'Connor,
director of the London-based Coronary Prevention Group:
   O'Connor told the British domestic news agency Press Association
in an interview: ``I do not believe this single research study
provides a proper basis on which to change well-established medical
advice to eat less saturated fat.''
   He said a 1,300-page study by the U.S. National Academy of
Sciences, released last month, showed there is no relationship
between low cholesterol and cancer.
   ``Our advice would be that people should eat less saturated fat
if they want to live longer.''
   Boston University microbiologist Selwyn Broitman told the
American Cancer Society's science writers' seminar in Irvine,
Calif., on Tuesday that he has found bowel cancer can lower
cholesterol in rats.
   A long-term study of residents of Framingham, Mass., revealed
some people have low levels of cholesterol and an above-average
risk of colon cancer, said John Laszlo, the American Cancer
Society's senior vice president for research.
   But he said studies of entire populations in several nations
show that people who eat high-fat, high-cholesterol diets tend to
have a higher incidence of both heart disease and colon cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
