<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Submarine     04-08 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Submarine,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells Thatcher Risk of Contamination From Sub Slight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Sub, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher early today that the risk of explosion
or contamination from a Soviet sub that sank off Norway was
``negligible,'' her office said.
   The Soviet leader also assured Mrs. Thatcher that the reactors
on the nuclear-powered submarine had been shut down before the
vessel caught fire and sank 312 miles off northern Norway, the
prime minister's office said.
   Gorbachev sent the message by telephone from his private office
in Moscow a few hours after he returned to Moscow from a two-day
visit to London where he held wide-ranging talks with Mrs.
Thatcher, her office said.
   Office staff at 10 Downing Street said it understood similar
messages from Gorbachev's office were sent to President Bush and
Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland.
   The Soviet leader told Mrs. Thatcher that there had been loss of
life but gave no figures, Downing Street said. Reports indicate at
least 12 crew are dead of the estimated 95 crew that were on board
the ``Mike'' class sub.
   In response, Mrs. Thatcher's office said it conveyed to
Gorbachev ``her condolences and sympathy for the families of those
who lost their lives in the accident.''
   The Soviet Union said today that the submarine sank in
international waters 110 miles southwest of Bear Island in the
Norwegian Sea. The Tass news agency said a rescue operation was
under way for other crewmen.
   ``Specialists ruled out the possibility of a radioactive
contamination of the environment,'' Tass said.
</TEXT>
