<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianRelic     04-08 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Relic,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Museum Rejects Indian Claim on Sacred Bundle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Museum of Natural History has
refused to give a more than 150-year-old relic to a Cree Indian who
ran 2,700 miles in his quest to retrieve the sacred object for his
people.
   Museum spokesman Herbert Kurz said Friday that the museum sent a
letter to Jim Thunder's home in Edmonton, Canada, notifying him of
the museum's decision.
   Thunder said he was a great-great-grandson, through adoption, of
Chief Big Bear, the Cree leader who created the artifact _ a sacred
calico-wrapped bundle holding bear claws, sweet grass and a plug of
tobacco. It was meant to give his people spiritual strength and
guidance.
   Thunder said Big Bear told him ten years ago, through dreams and
visions, to retrieve the bundle and take it to his tribe in Western
Canada where it would be used in prayers and sacred Indian
ceremonies.
   Told of the museum's refusal to give him the bundle, Thunder
said: ``I had been anticipating this.''
   He declined to say if he would continue efforts to retrieve the
artifact.
   Thunder, 38, arrived in New York March 21 after a run across
Canada, beginning in Edmonton Sept. 1, to draw attention to his
mission.
   In New York, he met with museum officials and formally requested
that the Cree artifact be returned.
   Big Bear made the bundle when he was about 13 years old and
later wore it into battle for protection and guidance.
   A son of Big Bear _ Joe Pimi, who was also known as Horse Child
_ sought out a museum anthropologist who was leading an expedition
into central Canada and on Sept. 10, 1934, presented it to the
museum for safekeeping, the museum said.
   Since then, it has been available only to researchers, scholars
and American Indians. It has never been on public display.
   In rejecting Thunder's claim, Stanley A. Freed, a museum curator
who met with Thunder, wrote in his letter to Thunder ``it is our
responsibility to honor (Pimi's) wish.'' Freed also noted that
other Cree Indians claim they are entitled to the bundle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
