<FIRST>u i PM-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0424 04-08 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa, Cuba, Angola Meet for Emergency Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with South Africa, Angola, Cuba gathering
for talks, fighting continues. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa, Angola and Cuba gathered
for emergency talks today in a bid to halt the fighting
jeopardizing Namibia's independence plan, which one official
described as all but suspended.
   Officials from the three nations, along with U.S. and Soviet
observers, planned daylong talks at an undisclosed site north of
Windhoek.
   Battles between the South African-led security forces and black
nationalist guerrillas occurred for an eighth straight day today,
police said.
   At least 262 guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's
Organization and 28 members of the security forces have been killed
in the heaviest fighting of the territory's 23-year war, police
said.
   SWAPO officials outside Namibia have disputed the figures and
say many civilians also have been killed.
   South Africa called on the guerrillas to surrender by midday
today or face intensified security-force action, but there was ``no
indication whatsoever'' that SWAPO planned to lay down arms as the
deadline passed, police Chief Inspector Derek Brune said.
   The South African-installed administrator of the territory,
Louis Pienaar, said Friday there was a ``de facto suspension'' of
the U.N. independence plan because of the widespread fighting near
Namibia's northern border with Angola. He said elections planned
for November could be affected by the conflict.
   Pik Botha, South Africa's foreign minister, said he had informed
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar about a South
African decision to activate an unspecified number of additional
soldiers. A major reason for the move, Botha said, was that some
guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization were
approaching areas where white farmers lived.
   The United Nations has allowed South Africa to move a limited
number of army troops from their bases to support anti-guerrilla
police units, but Botha said Friday that the security forces ``at
the present level are not able to stem the incursion.''
   Botha emphasized that South Africa remained committed to
implementing independence in Namibia and that the U.N. plan had not
been formally suspended. The U.N. Security Council said Friday it
was satisfied that South Africa still sought to grant independence
to the territory it has ruled since World War I.
   After six months of an informal cease-fire, the fighting began
April 1, the day the U.N. independence plan and a formal cease-fire
took effect.
   South Africa claims SWAPO has sent more than 1,900 guerrillas
into northern Namibia since April 1 in violation of an accord
requiring the insurgents to remain at bases at least 100 miles away
in Angola.
   Col. Herman du Plessis, a territorial army officer, said an
additional 1,300 guerrillas were in southern Angola near the
Namibian border and were ``an immediate threat.'' SWAPO leaders
contend most of the guerrillas had been in Namibia for some time
and have no intention of leaving for Angola.
   Some U.N. officials have suggested that SWAPO field commanders
mistakenly thought their units could return unmolested to Namibia
as of April 1 and set up bases. Several captured guerrillas have
said they returned to Namibia in search of U.N. personnel and
expected no confrontations with the security forces.
   The U.N. has authorized 4,650 troops for Namibia, but less than
1,000 have arrived. Of that total, the only forces in the northern
battle areas as of Saturday were about 300 logistical personnel.
   SWAPO has been favored to win the most votes in pre-independence
elections planned for November under the U.N. plan.
   The way for Namibian independence was cleared in December when
South Africa, Angola and Cuba signed an accord calling for
withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops who have helped Marxist Angola
battle U.S.-backed rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     04-08 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Convenes Committee to Map Election Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-New Era</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa called on
top union leaders and opposition intellectuals today to help map
out a winning strategy for the parliamentary election.
   More than 100 members of the Citizens Committee, created in
December by Walesa to serve as a policy council to Solidarity,
squeezed around tables laden with sandwiches and cakes in a musty
church basement.
   ``Thanking you for our common great political and public
victory, let me ask you to make use of this victory so we can
choose together some way of putting freedom into practice so there
will be real effects,'' Walesa said.
   The Sejm, or parliament, passed bills Friday that enacted
economic and political agreements approved by Walesa and the
interior minister, Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, after two months of talks
between authorities and the opposition.
   The laws allow restoration of Solidarity, which was banned after
the December 1981 martial law crackdown, give Poland its first free
elections since World War II, and create the post of presidency.
   The new parliament will consist of two chambers: a newly created
100-member Senate and a 460 member Sejm. Elections to the Senate
will be freely contested while the communist party and its allies
will be assured 65 percent of the Sejm with 35 percent reserved for
independent, non-party candidates.
   ``We should try to win in the elections to the Sejm and the
Senate, win on the social side because it would be very bad if we
retreated from the field and were unable to cultivate those limited
possibilities,'' Walesa said.
   He said the Citizens Committee should be formalized so that it
could ask future opposition legislators to speak on behalf of
Solidarity.
   The meeting was also expected to consider potential opposition
candidates for the elections scheduled for June. In the past,
Solidarity urged election boycotts to express disapproval of
authorities' policies.
   The boycott appeals and public dissatisfication led to
increasingly low voter turnouts and finally to the devastating
rejection of a government referendum on economic reform in November
1987.
   The opposition agreed to participate in elections during the
round-table talks in exchange for the restoration of Solidarity's
legal status.
   While the opposition will field candidates for parliament, it
has expressed reluctance to enter the government where the Polish
United Workers (communist) Party and its allies still would have a
majority of ministers.
   Authorities first proposed talks with the opposition on
political and economic reform during the second nationwide wave of
strikes in August.
   Walesa refused talks until authorities agreed to accept a legal
Solidarity. The go-ahead came when the communist party approved
Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's recommendation to restore Solidarity at
a party plenum in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890408-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief 1stLd-Writethru a0448 04-08 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS two grafs to first item to detail allegations.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrat Readies Ethics Complaint Against Gingrich</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arkansas Democrat will file a formal
complaint next week that House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich
allegedly violated nine House rules.
   Rep. Bill Alexander circulated the complaint he drew up among
his Democratic colleagues on Friday, Alexander spokesman Lee Powell
said.
   Under House rules, the formal filing of such a complaint by
Alexander will force the ethics committee to take a vote on whether
to launch an investigation of Gingrich, a Georgia Republican.
   Alexander's action was seen as the beginning of a Democratic
counteroffensive against Gingrich, who last year filed the ethics
complaint that resulted in a lengthy investigation of Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   The ethics committee, known formally as the House Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, is nearing the conclusion of its
investigation of Wright and is expected to decide as early as next
week whether to charge him with violations of House rules.
   Allegations in Alexander's complaint center on an unusual
promotional deal for Gingrich's 1984 book, ``Window of
Opportunity.''
   The deal involved 21 investors who put $5,000 each into a
partnership formed to promote the book. In return for their
investment, the partners were promised half the publisher's
profits, but the publisher ended up losing money on the book and
the investors got a tax writeoff.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Environmental Groups Urge Bush To Drop Cason Nomination</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of conservation groups are asking
President Bush to withdraw his nomination of James Cason to oversee
the Forest Service because of what they call Cason's ``wanton
insensitivity'' toward the environment.
   The groups on Friday detailed a series of complaints about
actions Cason took as an acting assistant secretary at the Interior
Department.
   They said he had ``improperly'' applied pressure on the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service to keep the spotted owl off the
endangered species list and ordered the destruction of a Bureau of
Land Management draft report that said the owl was threatened by
logging in the ancient forests of the Northwest.
   The groups also said Cason had attempted to stop the Forest
Service from carrying out a congressional mandate to publish
regulations governing oil and gas leases in national forests and
was responsible for mismanaging an Office of Surface Mining permit
system that resulted in the waste of millions of taxpayer dollars.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Spokeswoman Says Maine Senator Will File Report</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, will file a
report required by federal law stating that the East German
government paid for one night's lodging at a conference he attended
in June 1987.
   Cohen was one of at least a handful of members of the House and
Senate who neglected to report travel expenses picked up by foreign
governments as required under the 1978 Foreign Gifts and
Decorations Act, The Associated Press reported this week.
   Several lawmakers said they were unaware of the law or confused
about its requirements. It calls for any gifts or travel expenses
paid by foreign governments to be reported on a form. Senators must
report gifts over $100; House members have a ceiling of $180.
   Cohen's spokeswoman, Kathy Gest, said on Friday that information
just received from the American Embassy in East Germany indicated
the cost of the hotel was $132.40, $32.40 over the $100 filing
limit. As a result, she said, Cohen would file under the foreign
gifts act.
</TEXT>
