<HEAD>Thirteen Inmates Escape From Dedham Jail; Four Captured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with fourth inmate caught; Picks
up 5th graf, `State troopers ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 state and local officials
using search dogs and a helicopter nabbed a fourth escapee early
this morning, hours after 13 inmates broke out of an overcrowded
county jail.
   Two inmates were captured late Friday after escaping from the
Norfolk County House of Corrections, state police said. A third
inmate was found today in the cellar of a home and a fourth was
arrested near downtown Quincy.
   The inmates were discovered missing during a 9:30 p.m. head
count and may have escaped about 8 p.m, state police Sgt. Peter
Quinn said. Authorities believe they escaped by cutting through a
jail wall.
   State troopers said they were concentrating their search for the
remaining inmates in the South Boston, Roxbury and Hyde Park
sections of Boston where many of the men are from.
   The inmates were clad in green prison garb.
   The Dedham jail is one of the most overcrowded prisons in the
state. It was the scene of a disturbance in February when a fight
among more than 100 inmates broke out in the recreation room and
several small fires were set.
   At the time, there were 262 prisoners in the jail that was has a
federally set limit of 172. The sheriff has received special
permission that allows the extra prisoners at the jail.
   Dedham prison officials declined to say how many are in the jail
now.
   ``Certainly the overcrowding is excessive,'' said state Rep.
Marie-Louise Kehoe, D-Dedham. She said the federal cap was the
result of a lawsuit filed by inmates about four years ago.
   ``But please understand that originally, when the jail was
constructed, it was built to accommodate 72,'' Kehoe said.
</TEXT>
