<HEAD>Women Sue Country Club Over Discriminatory Fees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-eight single women golfers have
sued a country club that they claim charged them thousands of
dollars more for memberships than single men were charged.
   The lawsuit filed Friday says the Newport Beach Country Club
charged single women members up to $8,500 more than men for the
same type of membership.
   The women were told in an April letter that they could convert
their ``single lady'' memberships to charter member status for
$3,000 or to founding member status for $12,000.
   Previous policies allowed single men to become charter members
for no additional charge or founding members for $3,500, according
to the lawsuit filed by attorney Gloria Allred.
   Clubhouse manager Jackie Morrissey declined to comment.
   The lawsuit also claimed that women were required to pay guest
fees for male guests while men frequently were not charged for
female guests. Also, men receive free refreshments in their locker
room but women were required to pay, it said.
</TEXT>
