<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Flood,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flooding Destroys Villages Near Afghan Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding in Iran swamped dozens of
villages in a province near the Afghan border and forced thousands
of people to flee, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Saturday.
   No deaths have been reported, an unidentified official at the
prime minister's office told IRNA, monitored in Nicosia.
   Flood waters inundated 35 villages in Sistan-Baluchistan
province, causing hundreds of thousands of dollars in damage to
farms, bridges, highways and buidings, he said.
   About 6,600 flood victims have been evacuated and military units
are still trying to rescue people from the inundated villages.
Boats, helicopters and an airplane worked around the clock to save
human lives, he said.
   The flood was caused by the unusual rise in the Hirmand and
Paryian rivers in southeast Iran, IRNA said. The report did not say
when the flooding began or what caused the rivers to swell.
