<FIRST>r a AM-Utah-Fusion     04-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Utah-Fusion,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utah Legislature Approves $5 Million Request For Fusion Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seeing a potential bonanza if two
scientists' claims of a new way to create fusion prove true, the
Legislature voted to appropriate $5 million to accelerate the
research at the University of Utah.
   Following assurances from Gov. Norm Bangerter that he wasn't
asking for a blank check, the Legislature on Friday approved the
funds but stressed that no money would be spent until the
experiment was confirmed.
   Neither of the two researchers who claim to have produced
nuclear fusion in a test tube, Stanley Pons of Utah and Martin
Fleischmann of the University of Southampton in England, was
present.
   Bangerter and other officials say their claim, if true, could
bring the state millions of dollars in patent and licensing
royalties.
   ``I want the state to get going. We're not asking for a blank
check. We just want to be able to expedite the process so that it
can take us where it's going to take us,'' Bangerter told a joint
session of the Legislature.
   Lawmakers also passed legislation creating a nine-member state
Fusion Energy Advisory Council to oversee the research.
   They approved the two bills overwhelmingly after hearing
presentations from University of Utah President Chase Peterson and
members of the state Board of Regents.
   Fusion is the energy source that powers the sun and hydrogen
bombs. The energy produced by nuclear power plants comes from
fission, which splits atoms. During fusion, they are joined
together.
   Ordinarily, fusion requires extremely high heat. But Pons and
Fleischmann contend that they sustained a controlled fusion
reaction at room temperature, using materials found in any college
laboratory, and produced four times the amount of energy required
to run the experiment.
   Their findings were immediately cited by some as the door to a
long-range, safe, cheap energy source _ if they are confirmed by
other tests and transferred to a large-scale project.
   However, some scientists have said they cannot duplicate the
experiment and doubt its validity.
   Legislators stressed that no money would be spent until the
experiment is confirmed.
   ``If you're asking if there is a possibility of a runaway train,
we haven't even gotten the train to move yet,'' said House Majority
Leader Craig Moody. ``Before a single dime is spent, we have to
have fusion confirmed.''
   The appropriations bill allocates $2 million for the current
fiscal budget and $3 million for fiscal 1990, and authorizes the
new council to spend up to $300,000 for legal services, including
patent research.
   Attorney General Paul Van Dam told the body he needs at least
$75,000 immediately to hire international patent experts to advise
the state on how to protect the process.
</TEXT>
