<FIRST>u w PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru a0415 04-08 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Talks Held as Eastern Deadline Approaches</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Tops with 5 grafs to update with talks resuming today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines is flying the bare-bones
schedule it has kept since a strike began last month while its
three unions and prospective new owners meet through the weekend in
hopes of making a deal to revive the carrier.
   The negotiations, which entered their second day today, center
on concessions sought by former baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth and his partners. But before agreeing to any wage and
benefit cuts the unions are seeking assurances the new owners have
a plan to bring bankrupt Eastern back to profitability.
   The two sides met most of the day Friday in sessions described
by one source as ``highly preliminary'' and focused primarily on
the language of the Ueberroth group's tentative agreement to buy
Eastern from Texas Air Corp.
   Talks resumed at about 10 a.m. today. David Shapiro, appointed
by a bankruptcy judge as examiner to oversee Eastern operations, is
mediating the discussions.
   Union officials said it was highly unlikely a deal would be
struck during the weekend. A deadline does loom, however.
Ueberroth's $464 million purchase agreement allows him to call off
the deal if he does not reach new contract agreements with the
unions by midnight Tuesday.
   ``This will take some time because it's not only money
involved,'' said an International Association of Machinists
official who asked not to be identified. ``How does our ownership
part shape up? How do we get our passengers back? What kind of job
security is involved?''
   IAM spokesman Jim Conley said the unions would have no statement
on the negotiations because both sides in the talks had agreed to a
news blackout requested by the bankruptcy judge overseeing Eastern.
   That judge would have to approve any sale of Eastern, which has
been all but grounded since the Machinists struck March 4. The
airline's pilots and flight attendants have honored IAM pickets.
   In other development, Texas Air filed a lawsuit Friday alleging
that takeover specialist Carl Icahn was trying to interfere with
the sale. The lawsuit in Fort Bend County district court near
Houston charges that Icahn has ``illegally communicated and
negotiated'' with the Eastern unions.
   Ueberroth, who made millions in the travel business before
entering the sports world as head of the 1984 Olympics in Los
Angeles, was not on hand for the Friday talks but was expected to
participate if significant progress is made.
   Representatives of the Air Line Pilots Association and the
Transport Workers Union, which represents Eastern flight
attendants, also are involved in the talks.
   The IAM struck Eastern after rejecting concessions demanded by
Texas Air.
   Ueberroth, according to sources, wants $210 million in wage and
benefit concessions.
   Wally Haber, general chairman of the Machinists District 100 in
Miami, which represents Eastern mechanics and ground workers, said
$210 million is the total amount of concessions requested earlier
by Texas Air, $150 million of that from Machinists. He said he did
not know if Ueberroth had adopted the Texas Air demands as his own.
   Haber said Machinists were willing to accept 15 percent wage and
benefit concessions.
   Union officials have indicated a willingness to accept
concessions provided Eastern was sold to a new owner. Also,
Ueberroth's agreements give employees a 30 percent ownership stake
in return for concessions.
   Eastern has been flying about 110 flights a day during the
strike. Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said the sale agreement
caused no noticeable increase in passenger loads Friday.
</TEXT>
