<FIRST>r w AM-Soviet-Freeze 1stLd-Writethru a0512 04-08 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Freeze, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs lead to CORRECT Gorbachev and 7th graf to CORRECT name
of Savannah River Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plenty of Reactors Available to Make Material for Nuclear Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even if the Mikhail S. Gorbachev keeps his
pledge to shut down three military reactors, the Soviet Union will
have at least 11 others able to make material for nuclear bombs,
according to experts and documents available in the West.
   Gorbachev, in his latest arms control gesture, announced in
London on Friday that the Soviet Union had shut down one
plutonium-enrichment reactor in 1987 and would close two more over
the next two years. He said his country would stop producing
weapons-grade uranium.
   The size and even the location of Soviet military reactors is a
closely guarded secret, and Gorbachev did not spell out which
reactors would be closed, and which or even how many would remain
open.
   ``The difficulty we have is that he has wrapped his program in
such a veil of secrecy that we cannot get a reading of how much
further he needs to go,'' said Tom Cochran, a nuclear physicist at
the Natural Resources Defense Council.
   ``On the uranium side, the United States had produced a huge
surplus of weapons uranium in 1964, and shut off all production of
that. What he is doing is do what we did 25 years ago,'' said
Cochran.
   The Soviets already have an estimated 115 metric tons of
plutonium and 500 metric tons of enriched uranium, mostly in the
32,000 nuclear weapons thought to be in their arsenal, said Cochran
and Stan Norris, co-authors of a book on the Soviet weapons complex.
   The United States has about 110 metric tons of plutonium, with
further production frozen because the only three U.S. reactors able
to produce nuclear weapons materials, at the Savannah River Site in
Aiken, S.C., have been shut down because they cannot be operated
safely.
   Cochran, who has extensive contacts with Soviet scientists and
arms control officials and travels regularly to the Soviet Union,
said he had advised the Russians to seek a freeze like the one
proposed by Gorbachev.
   ``We pointed out to them the timeliness of this, as the United
States prepares to make major commitment'' to spend an estimated $8
billion to build a new generation of weapons reactors at Savannah
River and Idaho Falls, Idaho.
   ``Gorbachev clearly has taken a step that sends a signal that
they are ready to enter negotiations on ending production of
fissionable materials'' used in nuclear weapons, said Cochran.
   U.S. officials were slow to respond to Gorbachev's proposal.
President Bush, at his news conference Friday, said he had not
analyzed Gorbachev's proposal, ``so I honestly can't tell you that
I know the full significance.''
   One government expert on the Soviet nuclear industry said it
appeared that the plants mentioned in Gorbachev's announcement were
being closed for safety reasons.
   ``My estimate is that he is making some political mileage out of
steps they have taken for safety reasons,'' said the official,
speaking on condition that he not be further identified.
   Intelligence analysts declined to divulge their data on the
Soviet nuclear weapons complex, but two officials with access to
the classified reports said the information provided by Cochran and
Norris in telephone interviews went significantly beyond what has
been disclosed in public.
   The Soviets maintain two major weapons complexes, one at Kyshtym
in the Ural Mountains near Chelyabinsk and the other at Tomsk, deep
in Siberia, said Cochran.
   Those two complexes apparently are the sites of 14 Soviet
weapons reactors mentioned by Assistant Secretary of Energy Troy
Wade in testimony before the House Armed Services Committee earlier
this year. It was not clear whether that number included the one
shut own in 1987.
   Six of the reactors, known as the Troitsk series, are located at
Kyshtym and are run by the Soviet Ministry of Medium Machine
Building, one of 12 Soviet defense industry ministries, according
to government officials.
   The actual number of Soviet reactors able to produce weapons
material may be much higher, Wade said, because they use
water-cooled graphite reactors, like the RBMK reactors at
Chernobyl, to make nuclear weapons materials as well as electricity
for civilian use.
   Two of the Troistsk reactors were built in the late 1950's, a
few years after the three U.S. nuclear weapons production reactors
at Savannah River, and could be ready for retirement, according to
one government analyst.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
