<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-08 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheriff Art Martinak is so proud of his new
jail he has invited 40 guests to spend the night for free.
   The stay in the Linn County facility includes private room,
breakfast and dinner, and a fresh change of clothes.
   ``The only thing we don't provide is candy on your pillow,''
Martinak said.
   As many as 40 people were invited to sleep at the jail on one of
two nights, April 21-22.
   No reservations, Martinak said. It's first-come, first-served.
   ``This will allow the public to get a feel for what it's like to
be incarcerated and to see the ins and outs of the building they're
paying for,'' said Lt. Dave Burright.
   ``It gives our people a chance to train with real live people
who don't pose a security problem, before they have to deal with
the real thing.''
   A jail open house is scheduled for April 23.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a 1984 geography test, 20 percent of
Kentucky's college students couldn't find the Ohio River on a map.
Many of them thought the Appalachian mountains were in Europe.
   But fourth- through eighth-graders at a contest Friday knew that
Ecuador was the world's leading producer of bananas and that the
Great Victoria Desert is in Australia.
   Ninety-seven pupils competed in the geography contest for the
chance to represent Kentucky at the National Geography Bee in
Washington on May 19.
   The winner, 13-year-old Joe Wong of Conkwright Junior High
School in Winchester, admitted his final question was relatively
easy.
   ``The Napa Valley of California and the Bordeaux region of
France have what agricultural product in common?'' the California
native was asked.
   ``They both grow grapes for wine,'' he answered.
   Many of the earlier questions were tough, though.
   ``What islands were formerly called the Sandwich Islands?'' one
boy was asked. He didn't know.
   ``In which direction do ocean currents circulate in the middle
latitudes of the Northern Hemisphere?'' The next pupil didn't know.
   `What two islands are known for their use of geothermal
energy?'' That one was missed, too.
   (The answers: Hawaii, clockwise, and New Zealand and Iceland.)
   The National Geographic Society organized the geography bees
partly because of the appalling scores of U.S. students of all ages
on geography tests.
</TEXT>
