<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Endure `Geraldo' In Appeal For Slaying Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The families of two women slain by
what police suspect is a serial killer went on a talk show in hopes
someone with information about the murders will come forward.
   Judy DeSantos, sister of Nancy Paiva, one of eight women found
slain around area highways, made her first trip by plane to tape
the ``Geraldo'' program with host Geraldo Rivera in New York.
   ``I would never fly before,'' Mrs. DeSantos said. ``It's my way
of saying, `Nancy, I'm trying.'''
   The families of Ms. Paiva and Robin Rhodes, another victim, flew
to New York to join Bristol County District Attorney Ronald A.
Pina, via satellite. The hourlong show taped Thursday night will
air April 20.
   Members of both families were apprehensive about appearing on a
national television show, but wanted to persuade those with
information about the case to come forward, said Jean Arsenault,
Ms. Rhodes' mother.
   ``This way, maybe it will reach a lot of people out there,'' she
said.
   ``Maybe we can reach some poor girl, just one person, who was
going on the same path as my sister. Maybe, when she sees what
we're going through, she'll think twice,'' said Donna Rogers,
sister of Ms. Rhodes.
   The eight slain women were all cocaine or heroin users, and some
were addicts, authorities say.
   Investigators believe the women, found along or near Route 140
in Freetown, Interstate 195 in Dartmouth and Route 88 in Westport
were killed by the same person or group of people working together.
   Pina said he believes the women probably knew their killer or
killers.
</TEXT>
