<SECOND>AM-People-Bench,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Johnny Bench Critical of Former Teammate Rose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnny Bench, the retired Cincinnati Reds
catcher who will be inducted into baseball's Hall of Fame in July,
stopped just short of calling for the resignation of Pete Rose as
manager of the Reds.
   ``Too many things are adding up,'' Bench, Rose's teammate on the
Reds for many years and currently a Reds broadcaster, said in an
interview Friday night with television station WCPO.
   ``Too many things are pointing toward Pete Rose and as a result,
baseball is starting to suffer. The evidence is so large right now
and aiming toward Pete in so many ways. All of the sudden we're
trying to find ways for Pete to step down gracefully. And that is
really sad.''
   Bench and Rose were teammates on the World Champion Reds of 1975
and 1976.
   Rose is being investigated by the Internal Revenue Service for
tax evasion and gambling, The Cincinnati Post reported Saturday.
   The baseball commissioner's office has been looking into the
gambling, and he could be suspended from the game, for life if it
is shown he bet on the Reds while he was the team's manager.
