<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-RecoveredOil     04-08 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Recovered Oil,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>What To Do With 15,000 Barrels of Glop?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of gallons of crude oil glop
scooped up from Prince William Sound are being loaded onto barges
and could eventually be sold and even used to pave highways, Exxon
said.
   As operations enter their third week, workers have recovered
more than 16,000 barrels of the 240,000 barrels spilled from the
Exxon Valdez. The oil sits in barges along with thousands of
gallons of seawater that have been seived, sucked, sopped and
strained. A barrel is 42 gallons.
   ``For every gallon of oil we recover, we get one or two gallons
of water,'' said Henry Beathard, an Exxon spokesman.
   Beathard said despite the waterlogged condition of the oil, it
has some commercial potential.
   ``Any oil that's in the water, you can separate it and get the
water out,'' he said.
   While Beathard said it wasn't clear what the oil might wind up
as _ maybe heating oil, maybe asphalt _ the re-refining task will
be done down in ``the lower 48.''
   ``We haven't decided which refinery it will go to, but we'll
probably move it down in barges,'' he said.
</TEXT>
