<SECOND>AM-Gulf War,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Orders Aid to Troops at Front Cut in 6 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini on Saturday ordered that aid to troops at the cease-fire
line with Iraq be discontinued within six months, Tehran radio
reported.
   Khomeini's order is the first indication Iran plans to cut its
forces along the 670-mile border with Iraq since the countries
halted their eight-year Persian Gulf War with a cease-fire in
August.
   ``Deplete supplies within six months and end the work,'' the
radio quoted Khomeini as saying in a letter to Hojatoleslam
Mohammad Ali Rahmani, head of the committee responsible for sending
aid to the forces at the front.
   The 88-year-old revolutionary patriarch appeared to be referring
to border supplies the government solicited from private citizens.
The radio statement, monitored in Nicosia, was unclear whether
Khomeini wanted the supply program stopped for all armed forces or
just the voluntary units known as the Basij.
   U.N. observers monitor the cease-fire, but separate
U.N.-sponsored talks for a permanent peace have made no significant
progress.
   Khomeini's directive follows meetings Thursday between Iranian
foreign ministry officials and U.N. officials to lay the groundwork
for a new round of peace talks between Iran's foreign minister, Ali
Akbar Velayati, and his Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz.
   Velayati and Aziz have agreed to hold a new round of talks in
the near future at an undisclosed site near U.N. headquarters, but
no date or exact venue has been set.
   The talks deadlocked over Iran's insistence that Iraqi troops
withdraw from Iranian territory, while Iraq insists that the first
step should be the clearing of the Shatt al-Arab waterway.
