<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Guerrillas Capture Eight Mountain Climbers, Suspect Some
As Spies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas said Saturday
they captured eight mountain climbers, including three foreigners,
on the country's tallest peak to check if any were military
informants.
   The Menardo Arce Command, a guerrilla unit of the Communist New
People's Army operating in southern Mindanao, said they also
detained the climbers also to protect them from rebel mines.
   But they said the three foreigners and the five Filipinos,
captured Tuesday, will be released soon because interrogation
showed they were not spies.
   More than 300 climbers were on 9,690-foot Mount Apo for a
mountaineering convention.
   ``The presence of foreigners in the area gave us reason to
suspect they were sent by the enemies in order to spy or study the
terrain ... all in the guise of mountain climbing,'' the command
said in a statement.
   The statement said the foreigners included Gerald Leo
Christopher Kennedy of Ireland, New Zealander Trevor James Anderson
and James Andrew Smart of Britain.
   The group apologized for the detention but said it was necessary
for the ``best interest'' of the mountain climbers.
   ``To protect it (the area) from enemy troops, we had earlier
installed various defense mechanisms, including booby traps and
land mines in several strategic points of the mountain trail,'' it
said.
   The rebel command said Mount Apo is part of rebel territory and
any person entering the area should first ask for their permission.
   Tuesday's incident was reported to the military only Friday,
said Maj. Antonio Inciong, regional chief of the military's civil
relations service.
   Among the detained Filipinos was the Rev. Vic Dimaranan, a Roman
Catholic priest, Inciong added.
   The climbers who trekked to the mountain were attending the
annual convention of the Philippine National Mountaineering
Federation, Inciong said.
   The state-run Philippine News Agency said the climbers were met
by some 100 guerrillas near Tudaya Falls on the outskirts of the
village of Baracatan.
