<HEAD>Gorbachev Sent Word to Bush on Submarine Sinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev sent word to
President Bush to inform him of the sinking of a Soviet nuclear
submarine, the White House said Saturday.
   Gorbachev sent a message through the State Department, telling
the president there was no possibility of explosion or
radioactivity from the submarine accident off the northern coast of
Norway, said White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk.
   He said Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin called the State
Department Friday night with the message for Bush from Gorbachev.
   ``The purpose was to inform the president of the soviet
submarine incident,'' Popadiuk said.
   ``Ambassador Dubinin relayed that the submarine had sunk, that
there were a number of casualties but that the possibility of an
explosion and radioactivity is excluded and that search and rescue
continues,'' Popadiuk said.
   White House National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft relayed
the message to Bush, who was at the presidential retreat in Camp
David, Md.
   Popadiuk said he knew of no Soviets request for U.S. assistance
and that the United States was not involved in cleanup.
