<FIRST>u m AM-WorldTrade     04-08 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Trade,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Agreement Reported At World Trade Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators at world trade talks on Saturday
settled a dispute over textile exports and other issues that had
held up a 2{-year effort to liberalize global commerce, a spokesman
said.
   Delegates adopted the accord in a closed session, said David
Woods, a spokesman for the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   In Washington, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said that
``a stalemate that has dogged the negotiations has been broken.''
   Negotiators were deadlocked in efforts to achieve a major
revision in the GATT under the Uruguay Round of talks, which began
in 1986 and are to run through 1990. The accord reached Saturday
will serve as a framework for further negotiations.
   GATT regulates world trade treaties and settles commerce
disputes.
   The accord, signed by 100 countries, includes settlements of
disputes over farm supports, textiles, intellectual property such
as patents and safeguards against sudden surges in imports,
officials said.
   Settlements in the other 11 areas of negotiations were reached
in December at a meeting in Montreal.
   On Friday, the European Economic Community announced it had
reached an agreement with the United States on the issue of farm
supports. The settlement became possible after Washington dropped
its insistence on the elimination of all farm subsidies.
   The agreement calls for an overall freeze on farm supports and
import barriers through 1990. It calls for countries to reduce
their subsidies in 1990 but does not specify by how much.
   Ms. Hills said she hoped the accord would result in a gradual
correction in the U.S.trade imbalance ``in the context of export
expansion rather than import contraction.''
   Under another agreement reached Saturday, delegates resolved EEC
objections to earlier draft language that the 12-nation group said
would remove textile and clothing barriers too rapidly. The
agreement calls for further negotiations will be held later this
month.
   Developing countries with large textile industries want liberal
regulations. Industrialized countries such as the United States and
EEC members are concerned about the impact a lack of restrictions
might have on domestic industries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
