<FIRST>r a AM-RampFestival     04-08 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ramp Festival,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Follow Your Nose, If You Dare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHWOOD, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you want to find Richwood in the next
few days, just follow your nose. It's the place that smells of
ramps, the wild, odoriferous leeks whose spring harvest was
celebrated Saturday.
   ``The total thing, it stinks,'' said Duke Cowell, a patrolman
for the Richwood Police Department and a ramp eater for all of his
42 years. ``You wanted to know the truth, didn't you?''
   The festival is billed as ``The Feast of The Ramson'' and pays
tribute to the strongly favored leeks that grow in the nearby
mountains. About 1,000 pounds of ramps were harvested this year and
boiled down Saturday for the annual feed.
   Two days of snow didn't deter thousands of out-of-staters
flocking to the little town.
   ``There were piles of people. There were probably more people
from out of state than there are in Richwood,'' Cowell said.
``Since the coal companies shut down, there's only about 3,300
people in Richwood.''
   The ramps, served with ham, sausage, beans, cornbread and
buttermilk in a meal at Richwood High School, emit a strong odor
that's been called both pleasant and malodorous.
   All agree the scent is long-lasting.
   ``The smell will last in town for four or five days, and that's
no joke,'' Cowell said. He advised a home remedy _ frequent
gargling with vinegar _ to clear the breath in only two days or so.
   He said he would begin gargling Saturday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
