<FIRST>r a AM-ChallengerMemorial     04-08 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Challenger Memorial,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Challenger License Plates Sales Pay For Mars Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of Challenger license plates
have already paid for a memorial to the shuttle's seven astronauts
and are helping to fund future trips to Mars, state officials say.
   The design on the license plate features the space shuttle
rising on an orange-and-white cloud into a blue sky. It was
conceived in the months following the 1986 shuttle explosion in
which the seven lost their lives.
   The plates, costing an extra $15, went on sale in January 1987.
More than 500,000 people have bought or renewed the plates,
bringing in $5 million in 1987 and about $4.5 million last year.
   The state Legislature designated a quarter of the money for
scholarships and another quarter for the Florida Technical Research
and Development Authority to research manned missions to Mars.
   The rest is going to build and maintain the memorial at the
Kennedy Space Center.
   ``To bring in $5 million in one year from these tags, without
any advertising or promotion, boggles my mind,'' says Ben Everidge,
head of the Astronauts Memorial Foundation in Titusville. ``We had
no idea the tags would take off like that.''
   The $5 million memorial, to be inaugurated in October, is 50 by
40 feet and will rotate to follow the sun. The names of the seven
Challenger astronauts, along with the three killed in the Apollo
fire and four who died in training accidents, were etched by laser
onto its reflecting surface.
   The monument will stand on raised ground in front of the
visitors center near the entrance to the space center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
