<FIRST>r a AM-What'sObscene?     04-08 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-What's Obscene?,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey To Determine What is Obscene May Itself Be Obscene: Council</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey to find out what the public
considers obscene may be too obscene for city sponsorship, some
City Council members say.
   ``I read just the first two questions and realized that some of
the very things we are trying to take off the shelves are now going
out as part of our questions,'' council member Bob Long said Friday.
   The draft version of a questionnaire reviewed by city officials
Thursday asks people their opinions of 15 sexual acts ranging from
heterosexual intercourse to bestiality.
   The purpose of the survey is to define contemporary community
standards as an aid in prosecuting pornographers.
   But council members are nervous.
   ``This is not what I understood the intent to be,'' said council
member Janice Rettman. ``When a woman from the polling firm stood
up in committee some time ago and read off a bunch of questions,
they were pretty innocuous _ not about three people on a couch.
This sounds almost like we're sending out pornography ourselves.''
   Council President Jim Scheibel wants each council member to
study the draft questionnaire prepared by Minnesota Opinion
Research Inc. of Minneapolis. He then wants the council to vote on
it one more time, probably next week, before the poll goes to the
public.
 
</TEXT>
