<FIRST>u i AM-HospitalKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 04-08 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurses Charged With Killing Dozens Of Patients With Medication</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf, ``But the ...'' to ADD reports
that killings took place over the past year. Pickup 4th pvs, ``Initial
reports ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Saturday said at least
three nurses killed dozens of patients with overdoses of insulin
and other medication.
   Franz Priessnitz, a senior police official involved in the
investigation, told Austrian Television the nurses killed the
patients for ``a kind of euthanasia.'' He said among those killed
were patients they considered disagreeable.
   ``But the fact that they were most seriously ill always played a
role,'' the official said, adding ``we have so far 30 to 32 cases
of killing'' patients.
   Initial reports said the killings took place over the past year,
but police gave no specific time frame.
   The three women were arrested for questioning Friday, and
Guenter Boegl, the Vienna police chief, said Saturday that they had
confessed. Boegl said more people could be apprehended.
   No formal charges were filed by late Saturday.
   Euthanasia, a method of causing painless death, is advocated by
some as a way to deal with people suffering from incurable painful
diseases.
   Josef Siska, head of the homicide squad, told Austrian radio
earlier Saturday the killing of the patients at Vienna's Lainz
Hospital ``not only consisted of the administration of medication''
but did not elaborate.
   Priessnitz said a 30-year-old nurse was suspected of killing up
to 20 patients. The other two nurses were 25 and 27 years old, the
Austria Press Agency reported, quoting unconfirmed reports.
   Priessnitz said the three nurses did not act jointly but
separately, although it was not clear what each knew of the others'
criminal acts.
   Boegl said all three nurses made confessions, ``which differ
essentially only as to the number of possible victims.''
   Alois Stacher, Vienna's municipal health councilman, notified
police after doctors found that a patient had recently received an
overdose of insulin that could have been mortal. The patient
survived, Stacher told Austrian television Friday.
</TEXT>
