<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Elections     04-08 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Elections,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Committee to Name Opposition Candidates for Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solidarity trade union said Saturday
it will field opposition candidates for every available seat in the
two-chamber parliament in the country's first free elections since
World War II.
   Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said the list of
candidates for the June elections should be ready by late April or
early May.
   The candidates will run under the Solidarity Citizens Committee,
a group of more than 100 top union leaders and opposition
intellectuals that has served as a policy council to Lech Walesa
since December. They will have the full support of the independent
trade union, a committee statement said.
   Solidarity has said it aspires to act solely as a trade union.
Committee members say their group was formed as a separate
political structure that shares the trade union's ideals.
   ``Solidarity will not organize the election campaign, it is not
going to take part in elections, but is asking the Citizens'
Committee to cultivate those open fields,'' Onyszkiewicz said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa led the committee meeting in a
Warsaw church one day after the Sejm, or parliament, passed bills
putting into law the economic and political agreements approved
Wednesday by Walesa and Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak.
The accords ended two months of talks between authorities and the
opposition.
   The laws legalize Solidarity _ banned since martial law was
declared in 1981 _ set free elections and create the post of
presidency.
   The new parliament will consist of a newly created 100-member
Senate and the 460-member sejm. Elections to the Senate will be
freely contested. The Communist Party and its allies will be
assured 65 percent of the seats in the Sejm, with 35 percent
reserved for independent, non-party candidates.
   The Communist Party, with majority control of parliamnet, also
would hold the presidency.
   The Solidarity Citizens' Committee formed subcommittees to deal
with campaign organization, access to radio and television,
coordination of candidates, and election newspaper and finances.
   Walesa delivered a short speech to open the meeting, which
lasted more than six hours.
   ``Thanking you for our common great political and public
victory, let me ask you to make use of this victory so we can
together choose some way of putting freedom into practice,'' he
said.
   In the past, Solidarity called for boycotts of elections to
express disapproval of government policies.
   The boycott appeals and public dissatisfication led to low voter
turnouts and finally to public rejection of a government referendum
on economic reform in November 1987.
   The opposition agreed to participate in elections in exchange
for the restoration of Solidarity's legal status.
   Authorities first proposed talks with the opposition on
political and economic reform during the a wave of nationwide
strikes in August.
</TEXT>
