<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt     04-08 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Extremists Riot In Egypt, 4 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police placed a mosque under government
control Saturday, one day after Moslem extremists clashed with
police after attending a prayer service at the mosque.
   Four people were wounded and 39 detained in the clashes Friday
in Fayoum, about 60 miles southeast of Cairo, said Maj. Gen.
Mohammed Ahmed Mahran, Fayoum's security chief.
   He said detainees included Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, a blind
preacher who was acquitted of charges connected to the 1981
assassination of President Anwar Sadat.
   Mahran blamed Abdel-Rahman for the violence, saying that for the
past eight months the sheik had ``incited his followers against the
government'' in sermons he delivered at Al-Shuhada Mosque.
   He said Abdel-Rahman, spiritual leader of a fundamentalist group
called Jihad that was blamed for Sadat's slaying, led Friday's noon
prayers at the mosque and again urged worshipers to agitate against
the government.
   After the service, Abdel-Rahman led a crowd of 300 to 400
worshipers from the mosque, Mahran said. Police opened fire and
used batons and tear gas against more than 300 rioters after they
fired pistols and hurled stones at police, Mahran said.
   He said a police colonel and three rioters were shot.
   Mahran said authorities decided Saturday to take Al-Shuhada
Mosque from private ownership, put it under control of the Ministry
of Wakfs, or Islamic charities, and appoint a new preacher as a way
to keep Abdel-Rahman from the pulpit.
   Abdel-Rahman was charged with 23 others with the assassination
of Sadat, who was killed at a military parade on Oct. 6, 1981.
Abdel-Rahman was accused of issuing a ruling directing his
followers to kill the president.
   A military court acquitted him and another defendant but
sentenced five to death and the remaining 17 to long prison terms.
</TEXT>
