<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flooding Threatens North Dakota; Snow in North Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a foot of snow blanketed the North Carolina mountains
Saturday while authorities in North Dakota rushed to complete a
series of dikes to protect Fargo from the rising Red River.
   Scorching temperatures continued in California, but the heat was
expected to break Sunday with temperatures in most coastal
districts back down to the 70s and 80s.
   Across the continent, up to 14 inches of snow have accumulated
in Macon County, N.C., and snow also was falling in Maine, New
Hampshire, and in the Rockies.
   Flood warnings were reported in Baton Rouge, La., where the
Mississippi River was 4 feet below flood stage, and throughout the
rest of the South. Flooding also threatened in New England, across
North Dakota and Minnesota and in Indiana, Illinois and Ohio.
   Along the Red River, residents of Fargo and neighboring
Moorhead, Minn., readied for the flood-swollen river's predicted
crest on Monday, 19 feet above flood stage.
   Dean Peterson, a spokesman for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers,
said work on an extensive network of dikes was virtually completed.
   ``Right now, we're pretty much done ... if everything maintains
the way it is,'' Peterson said Saturday.
   There were scattered rainshowers from northern Arkansas to
northern Illinois, from the central Gulf states to the lower Great
Lakes region, and from Georgia to Virginia.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.
EDT included half an inch at Chattanooga, Tn., .51 inch at
Marietta, Ga., and a third of an inch at Huntsville, Ala.
   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.
EDT included three inches at Eastport, Maine, and one inch at Mount
Washington, N.H.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with sunny
skies over southern and central Texas and much of the Southwest.
   Temperatures soared into the 90s in south Texas, while readings
dropped into the teens in northern Minnesota, Wisconsin and upper
Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 13
degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 106 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   Sunday's forecast called for snow from Wyoming through eastern
Colorado to Missouri, over the Great Lakes region and northern New
England. Showers and a few thunderstorms were expected to extend
from the Texas Panhandle to Arkansas, with fair to partly sunny
skies over the rest of the nation and windy conditions in the
mid-Atlantic Coast region.
   High temperatures were expected in the 30s and upper 20s from
the northern and central Plains to New England; above 70 degrees
from California and western Oregon through southern and central
Texas to Florida and southern Georgia; in the 80s across the
Florida peninsula, from central California to south central Texas;
in the 90s or above 100 degrees in Southern California and southern
Arizona.
</TEXT>
