<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detention of Former Leader Extended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district court in the province of
Kosovo extended the detention of an ethnic Albanian leader accused
of inciting last months's bloody clashes, a newspaper said Saturday.
   Azem Vlasi, who was arrested March 1, will be held for at least
another month, Belgrade's daily Vecernje Novosti said. The
newspaper said his lawyer's had appealed the decision.
   The court ruling came after prosecutors said an investigation
into charges of counterrevolutionary activity had not been
complete, the newspaper said. The charges carry the death penalty.
   Vlasi, 41, a former Communist Party leader, was arrested in a
crackdown on alleged organizers of ethnic Albanian opposition to
constitutional changes that went into effect March 28.
   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise about 85 percent of Kosovo's
population, say their autonomy is curbed by the changes, which give
predominantly Moslem Serbia more control over the judiciary,
schools and police.
   At least 24 people were killed, 200 injured and dozens others
arrested in clashes between police and demonstrators last month.
Emergency measures, including a dusk-to-dawn curfew, remain in
force.
   According to the newspaper, the curfew will be shortened on
Sunday and schools in Kosovo will reopen on Monday.
