<FIRST>r a AM-TankerCaptain-Suit 1stLd-Writethru a0541edIsiahThomas
04-08 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Captain-Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Second Mate Charges Hazelwood With Drunkenness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Amero, who...,' to CORRECT that he now lives
in Meredith, sted Amherst.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former second mate under the fired Exxon
captain implicated in the Alaskan oil spill says the skipper was
frequently drunk and failed to follow regulations, according to
reports published Saturday.
   Bruce Amero, who worked for Exxon for eight years, has a $2.075
million lawsuit pending against Exxon in New York state court
charging that Capt. Joseph Hazelwood and other superior officers
harassed him.
   In a lengthy pretrial depostion given 18 months ago, Amero said
that Hazelwood ``constantly ... appeared to be intoxicated'' when
he was in command of the vessel, The Boston Globe reported Saturday.
   Amero said Hazelwood held regular drinking parties in his room
on board ship, and added that he once saw Hazelwood throw four
empty quart bottles of Jack Daniels whiskey overboard.
   ``There's a bad joke in the fleet that it's Captain Hazelwood
and his chief mate, Jack Daniels, that run the ship,'' he said in
the deposition.
   Hazelwood was captain of the Exxon Valdez on March 24 when it
crashed into a reef and spilled more than 10 million gallons of oil
into Prince William Sound in the nation's worst oil spill.
   Hazelwood, 42, faces three misdemeanor charges in Alaska of
operating a ship while intoxicated, reckless endangerment and
negligent discharge of oil. He is free on $25,000 bail after
surrendering last week on Long Island, where he lives.
   Amero, who now lives in Meredith, N.H., also claimed that
Hazelwood ``falsified the deck logbook about fire and boat drills''
aboard his ships, the New York Daily News reported Saturday.
   He told the New York newspaper in a telephone intereview that
``I smelled liquor on him on a number of occasions.''
   The lawsuit, which charges that Amero was treated so badly that
he needed psychiatric treatment, is pending.
   It seeks $2.075 million in personal injury damages from Exxon,
charging that he was ``subjected to abuse and harassment by his
superior officers and other supervisory employes, and in particular
Capt. Joseph Hazelwood.''
   There was no answer Saturday at Amero's home in New Hampshire.
Michael G. Chalos, Hazelwood's attorney, declined to comment on the
lawsuit.
   On March 24, Hazelwood allegedly turned control of the Valdez
over to a third mate uncertified to pilot the vessel in the waters
off Alaska. He was fired by Exxon on March 30 after the National
Transportation Safety Board said tests taken about nine hours after
the disaster showed he was under the influence of alcohol.
   Amero said his problems with Hazelwood began a week after he
first began working under his command.
   ``I was asleep and he was jumping up and down on his floor one
evening screaming at me to come up and drink with him,'' he said in
the deposition quoted in The Boston Globe. He said he refused and
that Hazelwood began harassing him, and that a female seaman told
him that she was sexually harassed by Hazelwood.
</TEXT>
