<FIRST>r i AM-India-Gandhi     04-08 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Gandhi,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikhs Arrested in Connection with Gandhi Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Sikhs charged with conspiracy in the
1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi were arrested
Saturday, police said.
   Police Commissioner Arvind Inamdar said Jagmohan Singh Tony, 35,
and Dalip Singh, 55, both college lecturers in Bombay, were
arrested at their homes.
   The men and three other Sikhs were charged Friday in a New Delhi
court with waging war against the state, sedition, criminal
conspiracy, murder and attempted murder.
   Two of the other Sikhs charged are in police custody and the
third was killed in 1985 by rival Sikh militants.
   If convicted, the four still alive face a sentence of death by
hanging.
   Inamdar said the five are accused of plotting Mrs. Gandhi's
assassination and other ``sensational acts to create chaos,
confusion and anarchy,'' as revenge for the June 1984 army raid on
the Golden Temple, the Sikhs' holiest shrine.
   They also are accused of organizing the July 1984 hijacking of
an Indian Airlines plane and plotting an abortive assassination of
Mrs. Gandhi and her son Rajiv in September of that year. Rajiv
Gandhi was elected prime minister after his mother's death.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed in the garden of her New Delhi
residence by two Sikh bodyguards on Oct. 31, 1984. One of them was
killed by other bodyguards and the second was convicted of murder
and hanged.
   Another Sikh was convicted of conspircay in the murder and also
hanged.
   The army raid on the Golden Temple was ordered by Mrs. Gandhi to
oust separatist Sikh militants entrenched in the shrine. At least
1,200 people, many of them Sikhs, died in the action.
   Sikh militants began fighting for a separate nation in 1982,
citing discrimination by Hindus, who make up 80 percent of India's
population.
   The campaign has worsened since Mrs. Gandhi's death. In 1988, at
least 2,400 people were killed in Punjab and at least 480 have died
so far this year.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are
in a majority in the northern state of Punjab, which borders
Pakistan.
</TEXT>
