<FIRST>r a AM-CollegeDiscrimination     04-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Discrimination,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>URI Treated Eight Woman Faculty Unfairly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have found the
University of Rhode Island guilty of violating antidiscrimination
laws in the cases of eight women faculty members, the college
president said.
   The Department of Labor concluded that the college unfairly
failed to promote two female associate professors to the rank of
full professor, according to a report released Friday by URI
President Edward D. Eddy.
   The school was also cited for failures in the areas of granting
maternity leaves, pay equity and job assignments in cases involving
six other women teachers or administrators, the report said.
   Eddy attributed the lapses to ``procedural errors'' and said
remedies had been taken, including the promotion of the two women
who had not been ranked as full professors.
   An investigation found that the university sought more letters
of recommendation when reviewing one woman associate professor for
promotion than it does for ``similarly situated males.'' It also
determined the college did not develop an adequate maternity leave
policy to ensure that women faculty would not be penalized for time
away from work because of childbearing.
   ``These are procedural errors which occured,'' said Eddy.
``There's no clear and concise proof of any pattern of
discrimination.''
   But William Rosen, faculty union president, said the report
shows URI officials ``haven't unlearned their former practices,''
referring to a sex discrimination lawsuit against URI that was
settled for $1.3 million in 1985.
   ``They're jerking people around, mainly women,'' he said.
   The 14-page report was the cullmination of a routine
investigation of URI's affirmative action policies. The Labor
Department's Office of Federal Contract Compliance undertakes such
reviews when agencies are slated to receive at least $1 million in
federal grants.
   If URI fails to comply with the report, the Labor Department
could take steps to cut federal funds to the 13,000-student school.
The grants total more than $30 million in research alone.
   Eddy said pay adjustments totaling $6,365 have been awarded to
five of the eight women involved and both associate professors
cited in the report have been promoted, Eddy said.
</TEXT>
