<FIRST>r a AM-SoCalHeat 1stLd-Writethru a0570 04-08 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SoCal Heat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0570,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Moderates But Heat Still Sends Throngs to Beach</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with heat-related death reported.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `In the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High pressure over California weakened
Saturday and let ocean air move onshore, but temperatures still
rose to record levels for early spring. One person apparently died
from the heat.
   ``The beach is packed,'' lifeguard Randy DeGregori said as an
estimated 100,000 people stretched out on Santa Monica Beach in
soothing 77-degree air temperatures or took a cold plunge into the
64-degree water.
   ``The crowd is just unbelievable, you'd think it was the Fourth
of July,'' said lifeguard Lt. Tom Hargett at Hermosa Beach,
watching over part of an estimated 300,000 people lining the sands
of the south Santa Monica Bay.
   ``I had to look at the calendar just to make sure it was
April,'' he said.
   The Los Angeles civic center temperature hit 89 at noon, tying
the April 8 record high established in 1987. Downtown had a
record-tying 100 on Tuesday and record highs of 105 Wednesday, 106
Thursday and 100 Friday.
   The heat contributed to the death of a Los Angeles woman, who
was taken to a hospital with heat exhaustion and later died of a
heart attack, police Sgt. Robert Normandy said.
   Barbara Zavaleta, 50, of Boyle Heights, died Friday evening at
White Memorial Medical Center, he said.
   In the desert, Palm Springs baked in 106-degree heat and the
town of Thermal fried at 105 by noon. Elsewhere, central and
southern areas of the state had noon readings in the high 80s and
90s.
   The highest temperatures moved into the inland valleys and to
the desert as the normal cooling sea breezes reasserted themselves
and kept most of the coastal highs in the 70s, 80s and 90s rather
than the triple-digit range.
   Throngs packed the beaches from Los Angeles to San Diego
throughout the week, and lifeguard agencies have had to call in
their troops to handle crowds rivaling those of summer.
   ``This is an early start,'' DeGregori said. ``We do get some
good (spring) weather, but this is something that you'd see in the
first week of July and the end of June.
   ``Every day this week, and today is no exception, we've used
every man available,'' he said.
   Lifeguards made hundreds of rescues during the week, Hargett
said.
   Southern California beaches are still uneven from the winter
waves, with deep holes lurking beneath the early spring surf, and
riptides.
   ``We've had rips running 2, 3, 400 yards out, like a freight
train grabbing people and yanking 'em right out,'' Hargett said.
Riptides run opposite to the ordinary flow and can pull people
seaward.
   Downtown Los Angeles got the first indication of a return to
normal when the overnight low fell to 67 by 5 a.m. Saturday, the
first time the temperature had dropped below 70 since Tuesday.
</TEXT>
