<FIRST>r a AM-SovietFlagFlap 1stLd-Writethru a0561 04-08 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Flag Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0561,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arkansas Workers Irked By Soviet Flag</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `The women ..., and 12th graf, `Ms. Kahn ...,
to CORRECT that trip was sponsored by Soviet-American Women's Exchange,
sted Peace Links.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINE BLUFF, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet flag fluttering over a paper
factory made some employees see red, but organizers of a weekend
visit to town by five Soviet women said Saturday the flag was a
friendly greeting.
   International Paper Co. always runs up foreign flags for
overseas visitors, said spokesman Gary O'Rielly.
   Valentina Matvienko, vice mayor of Leningrad and leader of the
delegation, said the women appreciated the gesture and were
``grateful to the citizens of Pine Bluff for their hospitality and
friendliness toward our delegation.''
   Employees circulated a petition Friday questioning the flying of
the flag, but did not get a response from the plant's management.
O'Rielly said he never saw a petition.
   Paper worker Albert Bolls said it was upsetting to see the flag
when he ended his shift Friday night.
   ``I don't think there ought to be a Russian flag flying over an
American plant. I'm a veteran and I don't like it. Russia is a
communist country and we're not,'' Bolls said.
   Another employee, Cathy Yiengst, said she understood the gesture
but didn't think it was necessary. ``I don't think you'd see an
American flag flying in their country,'' she said.
   Ms. Matvienko said that when Americans visit the Soviet Union,
``we also greet them by putting up their flags and regard it as a
sign of friendship.''
   O'Rielly said the firm had flown the flags of delegations from
other countries, including Japan and Finland, when they toured the
plant.
   The women had considered touring the mill on Saturday, but opted
instead for shopping at a local mall, said Marion Kahn of the
Soviet-American Women's Exchange, organizers of the Soviet women's
11-day tour of Arkansas.
   The decision had nothing to do with the workers' grumbling about
the flag, Ms. Kahn said.
   Ms. Kahn said she hoped the plant workers would look beyond
differences between the two nations.
   ``I can understand that some people might feel the way they do,
and that's the whole point of the trip _ for us to get to know each
other on a person-to-person level,'' Ms. Kahn said.
   ``The flying of the flag is certainly not a political statement.
We are trying to create friendships.''
</TEXT>
