<FIRST>r i AM-CostaRica-Figueres 1stLd-Writethru   04-08 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Figueres, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0547,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Costa Rican President Gravely Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS to update with condition of former president, changes
to conform and adds more background. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jose Figueres, who
in 1948 abolished Costa Rica's armed forces, is gravely ill in a
local hospital and has received the last rites, his doctor said
Saturday.
   Dr. Jaime Gutierrez said the 83-year-old ex-president was
admitted Friday night to San Juan de Dios Hospital after suffering
severe chest pains.
   He said Figueres ``is in the coronary unit and we are afraid he
might die.''
   Another doctor, who asked not to be identified by name, said
Figueres' condition was worsening.
   ``His heart cannot take a pacemaker. His situation is worsening
because he has a pulmonary infection and also has an inflamation in
a vein in one of his legs,'' the doctor said.
   Alberto Casals, a Roman Catholic priest, told reporters at the
hospital that he had delivered last rites to the man considered by
many to be the father of democracy in Costa Rica.
   Five of Figueres' six children and his two former wives were at
the hospital along with some government officials, hospital sources
reported.
   An adviser to President Oscar Arias said the president may cut
short a trip to Canada if Figueres' condition continues to worsen.
   In 1948, after allegedly fraudulent elections, Figueres went
into the hills with a band of rebels and led a brief but bloody
revolution that overthrew President Fernando Calderon Guardia who
had allied himself with the Communist Party.
   Figueres took over as president of a provisional junta for a
year, banning the communists and overseeing the writing of a new
constitution that provided increased social services.
   He also abolished the armed forces, making Costa Rica the only
nation in Latin America _ and one of the few in the world _ without
a military. Since then Costa Rica has been Central America's most
enduring democracy.
   Figueres served a second presidential term from 1953 to 1958 and
a third from 1970 to 1974.
</TEXT>
