<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GrocerKilled     04-08 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grocer Killed,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Drug Dealer Arrested In Slaying Of Anti-Drug Grocer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer who feuded with a
neighborhood grocer has been arrested and charged with
masterminding the slaying of the outspoken anti-drug crusader,
police said.
   Bobbie Lee Robinson, 29, was arrested Friday night and charged
with one count of first-degree murder and two counts of attempted
first-degree murder.
   One bystander was critically wounded and another managed to
dodge bullets in the machine-gun attack outside Lee Arthur
Lawrence's West Perrine grocery March 20.
   Lawrence, 51, died in a spray of 30 bullets that residents of
West Perrine say came in retaliation for his outspoken efforts
against drug dealers in the low-income community about 10 miles
south of Miami. Police also pursued the theory that the slaying was
the latest in an ongoing drug-related feud.
   Less than a week before he died, Lawrence reported to police a
death threat. His family said it was Robinson who threatened to
kill the grocer.
   ``Mr Robinson was in fact the party who paid the other subjects
that were involved to kill Mr. Lawrence,'' said Metro-Dade police
spokeswoman Lisette Williams.
   Two men are already in custody and another suspect is still
being sought.
   Metro-Dade Sgt. Ted MacArthur, supervisor of the homicide
investigating team, said he won't release the motive or the murder
fee until the remaining suspect has been arrested. But he said late
Friday that Robinson contracted with Rodney Newsome and Ronnie
Johnson to kill Lawrence.
   Newsome and Johnson, both 21, were arrested last week.
   Robinson has been charged seven times in five years with
felonies, including a 1984 conviction in Louisiana for possession
of cocaine with intent to sell. He was given five years' probation.
</TEXT>
