<FIRST>r a AM-HeartTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0576 04-08 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heart Transplant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0576,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Set Survival Record for Heart Assist Pump Gets Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with patient's condition,
include name of hospital. Pick up 3rd graf pvs, `Dr. Bud ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man received a new heart after living a record
132 days with a device that helped his ailing heart pump blood.
   Louis Wilson, a 39-year-old paper mill worker from Winnfield,
La., was feeling well enough to sit up in bed for an hour Saturday,
two days after his transplant operation, his wife, Carolyn, said.
   Finding a proper heart donor for Wilson was difficult because of
his large size and type B blood, doctors at Texas Heart Institute
said. Officials at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital didn't identify
the donor other than to say the person was from the Houston area.
   Dr. Bud Frazier, director of the institute's cardiac transplant
program, said Wilson, who is 6 feet tall and weighed 210 pounds
when he was outfitted with the heart pump, was ``doing fine'' after
Thursday's transplant.
   Wilson is thought to have survived longer than any other patient
who has used a stationary heart assist pump, which serves much the
same function as an artificial heart while the patient awaits a
transplant. The pump, however, assists rather than replaces the
heart.
   Wilson was hospitalized Nov. 21 with ischemic cardimyopathy, a
degenerative condition that prevents his heart from pumping enough
blood.
   On Nov. 25, a team led by Dr. O.H. Frazier implanted the
air-powered heart assist pump into his abdomen.
</TEXT>
