<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonLawsuit     04-08 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Lawsuit,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Dealers Sue Company, Say They're Cheated Out of Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry group of Texas Exxon service station
owners filed suit against the oil giant, charging that Exxon's
manipulative practices take profits from dealers and saddle
consumers with high fuel prices.
   The 19 Exxon dealers, most from the Houston area, charged the
nation's largest oil marketer with 15 counts of civil violations of
Texas antitrust and deceptive trade practices laws.
   The lawsuit was filed Friday in state district court. A
spokesman for the dealers' group said the action was unrelated to
the Exxon Valdez oil disaster in Alaska.
   ``We finally had enough of it, and we're fighting back,'' said
the spokesman, Exxon dealer Clyde Hall of Pasadena, Texas.
   An Exxon spokesman did not answer a telephone call from The
Associated Press on Saturday.
   The lawsuit seeks more than $5 million in actual damages and
unspecified punitive damages.
   Hall and his fellow dealers complained that Exxon favors select
franchises with ``sweetheart'' rents, interferes with dealers'
ability to buy gasoline cheaper from wholesalers and has rigid
rules for the inheritance of dealers' stations when they die.
   Exxon is the second oil company sued by its dealers in the last
six months. Last September, Texaco was hit with a suit on a
separate set of complaints by a band of dealer franchises in
Houston federal court.
   ``Is this the last of this type of suit you're going to see?
No,'' said Glenn Nilsson, executive director of the Lone Star
Service Stations Association, a dealer lobby.
   Lone Star lobbyist Wayne Konitshek, who helped the Exxon dealers
coordinate their suit, said more than 80 lawsuits for similar
alleged franchise violations are pending in nine states.
   Herb Fortson, attorney for the Exxon and Texaco dealers' suit,
said it took more than nine months to gather evidence and prepare
the Exxon suit.
   ``None of these dealers likes to fight their suppliers,'' he
said. ``But when the supplier is taking money out of their pockets
and favoring (a few) dealers, they have no choice.''
</TEXT>
