<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-ForeignPolicy     04-08 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Foreign Policy,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Policy Report to Bush Recommends No Major Initiatives Regarding
Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major foreign policy report to President
Bush advises no major new initiatives toward the Soviet Union, an
administration official said Saturday.
   Bush asked his advisers to ``take another look another time at
the whole situation'' after receiving recommendations on relations
with the Soviet Union, Eastern Europe, and East-West relations,
said the official. The trio of reports are part of a major foreign
policy review Bush initiated as he took office in January.
   In relations with the Soviet Union, ``I don't see anything
new,'' the official said, adding that there apparently was ``not
much to change right now.'' The reports were given to Bush during
meetings of the National Security Council over the past 10 days,
the official said.
   The reports recommended some changes, including new measures
involving an easing of pressure on Poland, the official said,
adding that regarding Afghanistan, the most likely option was to
break off diplomatic relations with the government in Kabul. The
official did not give further details.
   Meanwhile, The New York Times reported in Sunday's editions that
the president's advisers suggested that he maintain a middle course
allowing him to view the policies of Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev skeptically while responding with some bold foreign
policy initiative of his own.
   The administration experts recommended a ``status-quo plus''
stance toward the many changes occurring under Gorbachev in the
Soviet Union, the Times said.
   The Washington Post said in its Sunday editions that the three
reports determined that the administration should closely follow
current policies toward Europe and the Soviet Union set by former
President Reagan.
   The Post reported that some senior administration officials
expressed frustration with what they considered a complacent view
of world affairs reflected in the reports. However, it said other
officials praised the process that produced the reports, saying
they were less rancorous than interagency meetings conducted during
the Reagan administration.
   One official said the report on the Soviet Union urged that U.S.
policy ``should not be designed either to help or hurt'' Gorbachev,
the Post said.
   The Times said the classified analyses were prepared by the
Central Intelligence Agency, the State Department, the Pentagon and
the staff of the National Security Council. They concluded that
changes in the Soviet Union would continue throughout the Bush
administration even if Gorbachev were replaced with another Soviet
leader, the Times reported.
   Bush and some of his top assistants, National Security Adviser
Brent Scowcroft and Deputy Security Adviser Robert Gates, have been
skeptical of some of the changes in the Soviet Union. But that
approach has been criticized by some experts as too cautious at a
time when the Soviet Union is undergoing monumental change that
could dramatically alter American-Soviet relations, the Times
reported.
   ``The real debate in the administration will be between the two
centrist positions _ the stand-pat school and the
seize-the-opportunity school,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., told the
Times.
   The report to the White House suggested that the president could
pursue dialogue for the two superpowers to combat terrorism jointly
and slow the spread of chemical weapons, the Times said.
</TEXT>
