<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Payette     04-08 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Payette,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former UPI Executive William C. Payette Dies Of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William C. Payette, a longtime executive with
United Press International and United Features Syndicate, has died
at the age of 75.
   Payette died of cancer Thursday at his Dallas home.
   Payette joined United Press, one of the forerunners of UPI, in
1936 and established the first radio Teletype delivery of news to
South America and the first daily overseas transmission of news
pictures.
   He also organized Movietone News.
   He was former national president of Sigma Delta Chi, president
of press clubs in Los Angeles, Dallas and New York and a member of
the Overseas Press Club.
   Payette was southwest division manager for UPI from 1961 to
1968, when he was named president of United Features in New York.
In 1978, he became chairman of United Media, the parent firm of
United Features and Newspaper Enterprise Association. He retired in
1979.
   Among the stories Payette covered were the first U.S. airliner
hijacking, in El Paso in 1961, and Hurricane Carla. He also helped
direct UPI's coverage of President Kennedy's assassination.
   Payette is survived by his wife, Virginia, a former syndicated
columnist with United Features, a daughter, a son and six
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
