<DOCNO> AP890408-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GingrichComplaint     04-08 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich Complaint,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrat Readies Ethics Complaint Against Gingrich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arkansas Democrat circulated an ethics
complaint among his Democratic colleagues Friday charging House
Minority Whip Newt Gingrich with nine alleged violations of House
rules.
   The complaint, drawn up by Rep. Bill Alexander, will be filed
formally with the House ethics committee early next week, Alexander
spokesman Lee Powell said. Committee members were given advance
copies of the complaint Friday, he said.
   Under House rules, the formal filing of such a complaint by
Alexander will force the ethics committee to take a vote on whether
to launch an investigation of Gingrich, a Georgia Republican.
   Alexander's action was seen as the beginning of a Democratic
counteroffensive against Gingrich, who last year filed the ethics
complaint that resulted in a lengthy investigation of Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   The ethics committee, known formally as the House Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, is nearing the conclusion of its
investigation of Wright and is expected to decide as early as next
week whether to charge him with violations of House rules.
   The nine allegations in Alexander's complaint center on an
unusual promotional deal for Gingrich's 1984 book, ``Window of
Opportunity.'' Details of the deal were disclosed last month, just
before House Republicans elected Gingrich to their number two
leadership position.
   On Friday, Gingrich said the complaint was ``clearly another
Democratic smear, and in this case a pathetically, poorly done
one.'' He said Alexander's complaint was poorly researched and
riddled with factual errors.
   ``It is certainly Mr. Alexander's right to file with the ethics
committee,'' Gingrich said. ``In this case, it so clearly is an
unresearched and unprepared document, and it so clearly demeans and
distorts the ethics process that I hope that respectable and
responsible Democrats will intervene.''
   The deal involved 21 investors who put $5,000 each into a
partnership formed to promote the book. In return for their
investment, the partners were promised half the publisher's
profits, but the publisher ended up losing money on the book and
the investors got a tax writeoff.
   Gingrich's wife, Marianne Gingrich, who co-authored the book,
has said she received less than $10,000 of the $105,000 raised by
the partnership for arranging the deal and coordinating the
promotional effort. She also received a $26 tax benefit from her
share of the partnership.
   Mrs. Gingrich said last month that the ethics committee had been
consulted before the partnership contracts were signed to ensure
that the arrangement did not violate any House rules.
   Alexander contends in the complaint that the promotional deal
may have violated House rules limiting outside earned income and
gifts that a member can receive. He said the deal also may have
violated House rules governing the use of campaign funds and
government resources and requiring disclosure of travel
reimbursements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
