<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     04-08 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0491</SECOND>
<UNK>Three U.S. Servicemen Discover Suspected Rebel Bomb Trap</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three American soldiers found what
was believed to be a communist rebel bomb trap on a road near Clark
Air Base, a U.S. Air Force spokeswoman said Friday.
   Capt. Donna Eggleston said the servicemen detected the suspected
trap Thursday in the village of Sapang Bato when they found a wire
running across a road that leads to a firing range near the base.
   The base, run by the United States, is about 50 miles north of
Manila.
   In Manila, President Corazon Aquino met with a U.S. delegation
evaluating human rights in the Philippines and said she regretted
that her government's rights record was viewed as no better than
that of Ferdinand Marcos.
   In the southern Philippines, a Roman Catholic priest and a
village official were shot to death by a soldier, church officials
said.
   Ms. Eggleston said the American soldiers were on their way to
the firing range when they spotted the wires on the road and turned
back to report their discovery to base authorities.
   When American and Filipino troops went to the area, they found
that the wires had been removed.
   Local police said the incident could have been a rebel plot
since members of the Communist New People's Army operate in the
area.
   In October 1987, communist rebels killed two American soldiers,
a retired U.S. Air Force soldier and a Filipino of U.S. descent in
almost simultaneous attacks near Clark. There had been no attacks
on Americans since then.
   In Manila, presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno said Mrs.
Aquino told a group of attorneys from Minnesota that her
government's human rights record has improved despite criticism
that violations are similar to those under Marcos' 20-year rule.
The lawyers were completing a 12-day tour of the country.
   ``The fact is we have restored democracy and that is the most
important factor,'' she said.
   Fraser, in a telephone interview with the Associated Press,
agreed.
   ``She reaffirmed her own commitmnet to human rights, but I think
the problem is how to translate this commitmnet to the lower levels
of the government out in the field,'' he said.
   Amnesty International and other human rights groups have accused
the military of continued human rights violations during Mrs.
Aquino's administration.
   On Mindanao island, the Rev. Dionisio Malalay and a village
councilman were gunned down Thursday in the town of Tabina, about
520 miles southeast of Manila, a church official in Manila said.
   The Rev. Dwight Calaar said Malalay was talking with councilman
Rufino Rivera when a Philippine Constabulary soldier and a
militiaman passed by and started an argument with Rivera.
   Malalay tried to intervene and the soldier shot him, Calaar
said. The militiaman then shot Rivera, he said.
   The Constabulary regional headquarters reported the shooting as
an ambush by communist New People's Army rebels.
</TEXT>
