<HEAD>Report Attempt To Kill Colleague Of Slain Ecologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen may have attempted to kill
a colleague of slain Amazonian ecologist Chico Mendes, police
reported Friday.
   Federal police chief Orion Alves said shots were fired Thursday
night at the home of Osmarino Amancio, president of the rubber
tappers union, in the jungle town of Brasileia 2,700 miles
northwest of Rio and on the border with Bolivia.
   ``We are aware of a possible assassination attempt and gunshots
outside his house but we don't know who fired them,''Alves said by
telephone from Rio Branco, the Acre state capital 155 miles from
Brasileia.
   He said Amancio was not hurt.
   Amancio, who has reported frequent death threats, is under
constant guard by four policemen, according to Alves.
   Amancio and Mendes led rubber tappers in movements to prevent
ranchers from cutting down virgin forests for pasture land.
   Mendes, a union leader who became a world-renowned ecological
consultant on rain forests, was shot to death Dec. 22 at his home
in Xapuri 40 miles northeast of Brasileia. A local cattle rancher
and his sons have been arrested and charged with the killing.
