<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 0648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv8-9   04-08 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 8-9,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions April 8-9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tough To Read Tea Leaves In Murky Concoction Of Economic Stats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forecasters gazing into their crystal balls say
the economic picture is still fuzzy but they have started to get an
image of how people are reacting to rising interest rates. A few
businesses probably don't like what they've seen so far.
   Car makers and big retail merchants furnished figures this past
week that cast shadows of doubt about their situations.
   Sales of cars and trucks in the United States skidded an
unexpectedly steep 18.3 percent in late March, auto manufacturers
reported, and many retailers didn't ring up as much business last
month as they had thought they would.
   The news was unsurprising given the direction interest rates
have taken lately.
   Expensive purchases normally financed with loans _ like cars _
were predicted to shrink as consumers became obliged to spend more
on things such as mortgage payments. So widely anticipated was the
spending slowdown that the nation's Big Three automakers cranked up
their promotional vehicles before the latest results were even in.
   They have been touting rebates and cut-rate financing deals,
including Chrysler Corp.'s zero percent financing, to tempt
customers back into the showrooms during the important spring
car-buying season.
   Historically, March and April are the months when shoppers gear
up for extra summertime driving by paying a visit to dealerships.
Many may have stopped by to browse in late March but fewer than
usual bought.
   Conventional wisdom says the incentives will breathe some oomph
into auto sales, but after a short while they'll lose gusto again
once bargain-hunters have had their fill.
   When many of nation's major retailers toted up March sales they
were disappointed. Some blamed bad weather or the fact that they
had one less selling day in this year's five-week period than they
had last year _ which can make a big difference.
   Retail industry analysts agreed with those points. But in
sifting through the numbers they came up with evidence that
consumers are losing enthusiasm to spend money on the types of
things they bought in abundance during much of the six-year
economic expansion.
   ``I think we have a fundamental switch in consumer spending,''
says Allen Sinai, chief economist at the Boston Co.
   Consumers are spending more on services, such as travel,
recreational pastimes or personal health and fitness plans.
   ``The kind of items bought at the chain stores are less
prominent in the consumer basket these days,'' according to Sinai.
   A calculation by the securities firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
indicated sales of specialty apparel, hard goods such as home
furnishings, and other general merchandise, rose just 4.6 percent
in March, down from February's 7.6 percent growth. In order words,
sales barely kept ahead of inflation.
   Retailers are justifiably reluctant to generalize based on only
one month's performance. The transition from winter to summer can
be an unsettled time for the weather, so shoppers frequently don't
buy clothes to freshen up their wardrobes or get new gardening
gear, for instance, until they're sure warm temperatures have come
to stay.
   April could be a cruel month for car makers and general
merchandisers if customers don't act on the traditional weather cue
and go out shopping.
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _The government reported what was desribed as an ambiguous set
of statistics about the labor market. The Labor Department said the
unemployment rate fell to 5 percent in March, a new 15-year low,
from 5.1 percent the month before, even though the number of new
jobs added to the economy fell to the smallest amount since August.
   _Eastern Airlines agreed to be acquired by an investor group led
by former baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth for about $464
million. But the deal, which would give Eastern's 30,000 employees
a 30 percent stake in the airline, won't become final until after
parent Texas Air Corp. brings Eastern out of federal bankruptcy
protection, among other things.
   _As junk bond enthusiasts capped an annual get-together in
California and toasted Michael Milken's pioneering efforts in the
high-yield, high-risk business, the former head of Drexel Burnham's
junk bond operation pleaded innocent at his arraignment in
Manhattan federal court on a raft of racketeering and securities
fraud charges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End of advance for weekend editions April 8-9</NOTE>
