<FIRST>r f AM-SoftwareSuit     04-08 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Software Suit,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Software Companies Sue Italian Firms For Copyright Infringement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. software consortium has accused
three Italian firms of pirating American programs in an
unprecedented copyright infringement suit, company officials said
Friday.
   The suit, filed Thursday in Milan by the Business Software
Association, accuses the European companies of copying without
authorization software produced by Lotus Development Corp. of
Cambridge and Ashton-Tate Corp. of Torrance, Calif.
   The Elettrocarbonium SpA, Montedison SpA and its affiliate,
Monefibre SpA, were named as co-defendants in BSA's suit, but
exactly what if any compensation the group was seeking was not
specified.
   BSA President Douglas E. Phillips said the group would likely
file additional lawsuits against several other companies in the
months to come.
   ``The level of unauthorized copying of software in Italy _ not
only by dealers but by organizational users _ is one of the most
egregious in Europe,'' Phillips said in a prepared statement.
   The breach had cost companies trying to develop and market
legitimate software hundreds of millions of dollars, Phillips said.
   Technical experts found evidence of widespread software
duplication during inspections ordered by the Italian courts and
conducted last week at two of the accused firms, Phillips said.
   He said more than 90 percent of the software inspected at
Montedison was reproduced without authorization and 80 percent of
the software inspected at Elettrocarbonium consisted of
unauthorized copies.
   Officials at the Milan-based Montedison and its affiliate have
denied the charges. BSA officials did not know whether
Elettrocarbonium had also denied the allegations.
   BSA spokeswoman Pilar Cloud said the accused companies pirate
the software by buying a single copy of a program and then
duplicating it internally and reselling it.
   ``It's a fairly common practice internationally, but it's very
illegal,'' Cloud said. ``BSA hopes to put a stop to it.''
   Washington-based BSA was founded in 1988 to promote free and
open trade in legitimate business software while protecting
intellectual property.
   The consortium's membership also includes Aldus Corp. of
Seattle, Autodesk Inc. of Sausalito, Calif., Microsoft Corp. of
Redmond, Wash., and WordPerfect Corp. of Orem, Utah.
</TEXT>
